 Out\" Named Best Picture of 2017 by Seattle Film Critics Society|date=December 18, 2017|website=Seattle Film Critics Society|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212163705/http://seattlefilmcritics.com/2017/12/11/blade-runner-2049-leads-the-2017-seattle-film-critics-society-nominations/https://web.archive.org/web/20171219120239/http://seattlefilmcritics.com/2017/12/18/get-named-best-picture-2017-seattle-film-critics-society/|archivedate=December 12, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[St. Louis Gateway Film Critics Association Awards 2017|St. Louis Film Critics Association]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| December 17, 2017\n| Best Production Design\n| Sarah Greenwood\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stlfilmcritics.org/awards|title=2017 StLFCA Annual Award Winners|date=December 17, 2017|work=[[St. Louis Film Critics Association]]|accessdate=December 17, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160504082034/http://www.stlfilmcritics.org/awards|archivedate=May 4, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Visual Effects\n| rowspan=\"2\"|''Beauty and the Beast''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"9\"| [[2017 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"9\"| August 13, 2017\n| [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie \u2013 Sci-Fi/Fantasy|Choice Movie: Fantasy]]\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"9\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref name=\"Teen Choice\">{{cite web|url=http://www.teenvogue.com/story/teen-choice-awards-2017-nominees|title=Teen Choice Awards 2017: See the First Wave of Nominations|last=Ceron|first=Ella|work=[[Teen Vogue]]|date=June 19, 2017|accessdate=June 19, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170620033558/http://www.teenvogue.com/story/teen-choice-awards-2017-nominees|archivedate=June 20, 2017}}</ref><br /><ref name=\"Winners\">{{cite web|last1=Ramos|first1=Dino-Ray|title=Teen Choice Awards 2017 Winners: \u2018Wonder Woman\u2019, \u2018Beauty And The Beast\u2019, \u2018Riverdale\u2019 Among Honorees|url=https://deadline.com/2017/08/teen-choice-awards-winners-2017-wonder-woman-beauty-and-the-beast-riverdale-fox-1202147975/|website=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=enske Business Media, LLC.|date=August 13, 2017|accessdate=August 14, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814101308/http://deadline.com/2017/08/teen-choice-awards-winners-2017-wonder-woman-beauty-and-the-beast-riverdale-fox-1202147975/|archivedate=August 14, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie Actor \u2013 Sci-Fi/Fantasy|Choice Movie: Fantasy Actor]]\n| Dan Stevens\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie Actress \u2013 Sci-Fi/Fantasy|Choice Movie: Fantasy Actress]]\n| Emma Watson\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie Villain|Choice Movie Villain]]\n| Luke Evans\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Choice Movie Ship\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Emma Watson and Dan Stevens\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Choice Liplock\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Choice Scene Stealer\n| Josh Gad\n| {{nom}}\n|- \n| rowspan=\"2\"| Choice Hissy Fit\n| Luke Evans\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Dan Stevens\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[16th Visual Effects Society Awards|Visual Effects Society Awards]]\n| February 13, 2018\n| Outstanding Virtual Cinematography in a Photoreal Project\n| Shannon Justison, Casey Schatz, Neil Weatherley and Claire Michaud for \"[[Be Our Guest]]\"\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/2018-visual-effects-society-awards-nominations-list-full-1067888|title=Visual Effects Society Awards: 'Apes,' 'Blade Runner 2049' Lead Feature Nominees|work=Hollywood Reporter|first=Carolyn|last=Giardina|date=January 16, 2018|accessdate=January 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180116220634/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/2018-visual-effects-society-awards-nominations-list-full-1067888|archive-date=January 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association Awards 2017|Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| December 8, 2017\n| Best Motion Capture Performance\n| Dan Stevens\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dcfilmcritics.com/awards/|title=The 2017 WAFCA Awards|work=[[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association]]|date=December 7, 2017|accessdate=December 6, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312055647/http://www.dcfilmcritics.com/awards/|archivedate=March 12, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Production Design\n| Sarah Greenwood and Katie Spencer\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Women Film Critics Circle]]\n| December 17, 2017\n| Best Family Film\n| ''Beauty and the Beast''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|title=The 2017 Women Film Critics Circle (WFCC) Nominations|url=https://www.nextbestpicture.com/latest/the-2017-women-film-critics-circle-wfcc-nominations|last=Neglia|first=Matt|accessdate=December 13, 2017|date=December 12, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213010140/https://www.nextbestpicture.com/latest/the-2017-women-film-critics-circle-wfcc-nominations|archivedate=December 13, 2017}}</ref><br /><ref>{{cite web|title=The 2017 Women Film Critics Circle (WFCC) Winners|url=https://www.nextbestpicture.com/latest/the-2017-women-film-critics-circle-wfcc-winners|last=Neglia|first=Matt|accessdate=December 25, 2017|date=December 22, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226130500/https://www.nextbestpicture.com/latest/the-2017-women-film-critics-circle-wfcc-winners|archivedate=December 26, 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Controversies==\n===Gay character===\nControversy erupted after director [[Bill Condon]] said there was a \"gay moment\" in the film, when LeFou briefly waltzes with Stanley, one of Gaston's friends.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2017/03/20/beauty-and-the-beast-gay-moment-audience-reaction/99407168/ |title='Beauty and the Beast's 'gay moment' may have been much ado about nothing |newspaper=USA Today |date=March 20, 2017 |accessdate=March 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910204317/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2017/03/20/beauty-and-the-beast-gay-moment-audience-reaction/99407168/ |archivedate=September 10, 2017  }}</ref> Afterwards in an interview with [[Vulture.com]], Condon stated, \"Can I just say, I'm sort of sick of this. Because you've seen the movie\u2014it's such a tiny thing, and it's been overblown.\" Condon also added that ''Beauty and the Beast'' features much more diversity than just the highly talked-about LeFou: \"That was so important. We have interracial couples\u2014this is a celebration of everybody's individuality, and that's what's exciting about it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/03/bill-condon-on-directing-beauty-and-the-beast.html |title=Bill Condon on Beauty and the Beast, His Musical Influences, and Lindsay Lohan's Plan for The Little Mermaid |publisher=Vulture |date=March 15, 2017 |accessdate=March 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170419051553/http://www.vulture.com/2017/03/bill-condon-on-directing-beauty-and-the-beast.html |archivedate=April 19, 2017  }}</ref> GLAAD president and CEO Sarah Kate Ellis praised the move, stating, \"It is a small moment in the film, but it is a huge leap forward for the film industry.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/glaad-beauty-and-the-beast-gay-moment-disney/|title=GLAAD president: \"Beauty and the Beast\" foes are \"outliers\"|author=Ned Ehrbar|publisher=CBS News|date=March 17, 2017|accessdate=March 17, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170419051558/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/glaad-beauty-and-the-beast-gay-moment-disney/|archivedate=April 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn Russia, [[Vitaly Milonov]] agitated the culture minister for banning the film,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/global/russia-ban-beauty-and-the-beast-josh-gad-gay-lefou-1202002198/ |title=Russia May Ban Disney's 'Beauty and the Beast' Over Gay Character |work=Variety |date=March 4, 2017 |accessdate=March 5, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170304203350/http://variety.com/2017/film/global/russia-ban-beauty-and-the-beast-josh-gad-gay-lefou-1202002198/ |archivedate=March 4, 2017  }}</ref> but instead it was given a 16+ rating (children under the age of 16 can only be admitted to see it in theaters with accompanying adults).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/03/06/beauty-and-the-beast-russia-lawmaker-ban/ |title=Russia won't ban Beauty and the Beast\u2014but will have an age restriction |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=March 6, 2017 |accessdate=March 7, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910205642/http://ew.com/movies/2017/03/06/beauty-and-the-beast-russia-lawmaker-ban/ |archivedate=September 10, 2017  }}</ref> Additionally, a theater in [[Henagar, Alabama]] did not screen the film because of the subplot.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/beauty-and-the-beast-alabama-theater_us_58b9a6f7e4b05cf0f400427b |title=Alabama Theater Won't Show 'Beauty and the Beast' Because of Gay Subplot |work=The Huffington Post |accessdate=March 3, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170306104238/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/beauty-and-the-beast-alabama-theater_us_58b9a6f7e4b05cf0f400427b |archivedate=March 6, 2017  }}</ref> In [[Malaysia]], the [[Film Censorship Board of Malaysia|Film Censorship Board]] insisted the \"gay moment\" scene be cut, prompting an indefinite postponement of its release by Disney, followed by their decision to withdraw it completely if it could not be released uncensored.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2017/03/13/beauty-and-the-beast-release-postponed-for-internal-review/|title=Beauty and the Beast release postponed for 'internal review'|last=Cheang|first=Michael|date=March 13, 2017|accessdate=March 15, 2017|website=The Star Online|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170314040844/http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2017/03/13/beauty-and-the-beast-release-postponed-for-internal-review/|archivedate=March 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/beauty-and-the-beast/news/a823340/disney-pulls-beauty-and-the-beast-from-cinemas-in-malaysi-until-further-notice/ |title=Disney pulls Beauty and the Beast from cinemas in Malaysia 'until further notice' |website=Digital Spy |date=March 13, 2017 |accessdate=March 13, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910204933/http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/beauty-and-the-beast/news/a823340/disney-pulls-beauty-and-the-beast-from-cinemas-in-malaysi-until-further-notice/ |archivedate=September 10, 2017  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Disney refuses to cut 'gay moment' from 'Beauty and the Beast' for Malaysia|website=Malay Mail Online|accessdate=March 15, 2017|date=March 15, 2017|url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/disney-refuses-to-cut-gay-moment-from-beauty-and-the-beast-for-malaysia|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910205012/http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/disney-refuses-to-cut-gay-moment-from-beauty-and-the-beast-for-malaysia|archivedate=September 10, 2017}}</ref> The studio moved the release date to March 30, to allow more time for Malaysia's censor board to make a decision on whether or not to release the film without changes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/disney-wont-cut-beauty-beast-gay-moment-malaysia-censors-986609|title=Disney Defies Malaysia Censors, Won't Cut 'Beauty and the Beast' Gay Moment|author=Mia Galuppo|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 15, 2017|accessdate=March 16, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910205050/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/disney-wont-cut-beauty-beast-gay-moment-malaysia-censors-986609|archivedate=September 10, 2017}}</ref> The distributors and producers then submitted an appeal to the Film Appeal Committee of Malaysia, which allowed the film to be released without any cuts and a [[Film censorship in Malaysia#Rating system|P13 rating]] on the grounds that \"the gay element was minor and did not affect the positive elements featured in the film\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/malaysia-clears-release-beauty-beast-gay-moment-intact-report-987588|title=Malaysia Clears Release of 'Beauty and the Beast,' with 'Gay Moment' Intact|author=Patrick Brzeski|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 21, 2017|accessdate=March 21, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910205127/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/malaysia-clears-release-beauty-beast-gay-moment-intact-987588|archivedate=September 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2017/03/29/film-appeals-committee-decision-to-release-beauty-and-beast/|title=Film Appeal Committee's decision to release Beauty and the Beast|newspaper=The Star Online|date=March 21, 2017|accessdate=March 30, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910205221/http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2017/03/29/film-appeals-committee-decision-to-release-beauty-and-beast/|archivedate=September 10, 2017}}</ref> In [[Kuwait]], the movie was withdrawn from cinemas by [[Cinescape|National Cinema Company]] which owns most of the cinemas in the country. A board member of the company stated that the Ministry of Information's censorship department had requested it to stop its screening and edit it for things deemed offensive by it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-39337844|title=Beauty and the Beast pulled from cinemas in Kuwait|publisher=BBC|date=March 21, 2017|accessdate=March 30, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328145707/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-39337844|archivedate=March 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe film also received criticism over its portrayal of LeFou, as many felt that it was used as a way of teasing LGBT+ viewers without providing adequate representation, with his \"exclusively gay moment\" being three seconds of him dancing with another man at the end of the film.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://screenrant.com/beauty-beast-power-rangers-gay-representation/|title=How Beauty and the Beast & Power Rangers Cheated Gay Fans|date=April 2, 2017|work=Screen Rant|access-date=October 21, 2017|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171021111628/http://screenrant.com/beauty-beast-power-rangers-gay-representation/|archivedate=October 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Belle and the Beast's relationship===\nDisney has sought to portray Belle as an empowered young woman,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Watkins|first1=Gwynne|title='Beauty and the Beast' Featurette Makes a Case for Feminist Belle|url=https://www.yahoo.com/movies/beauty-and-the-beast-featurette-makes-a-case-for-feminist-belle-180620182.html|accessdate=March 26, 2017|publisher=Yahoo Movies|date=March 2, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170419051635/https://www.yahoo.com/movies/beauty-and-the-beast-featurette-makes-a-case-for-feminist-belle-180620182.html|archivedate=April 19, 2017}}</ref> but a debate questioning whether it is possible for a captor to fall in love with their prisoner, and whether this is a problematic theme, has resulted.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Williams|first1=Zoe|title=Beauty and the Beast: feminist or fraud|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/mar/19/beauty-and-the-beast-feminist-or-fraud|accessdate=March 26, 2017|newspaper=The Guardian|date=March 19, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170419051751/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/mar/19/beauty-and-the-beast-feminist-or-fraud|archivedate=April 19, 2017}}</ref> As was the case with the original animated film, one argument is that Belle suffers from [[Stockholm syndrome]] (a condition that causes hostages to develop a psychological alliance with their captors as a survival strategy during captivity). Emma Watson studied whether Belle is trapped in an abusive relationship with the Beast before signing on and concluded that she does not think the criticism fits this version of the folk tale.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Blasberg|first1=Derek|title=Cover Story: Emma Watson, Rebel Belle|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/02/emma-watson-cover-story|accessdate=March 27, 2017|work=Vanity Fair|date=February 28, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170228194205/http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/02/emma-watson-cover-story|archivedate=February 28, 2017}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=August 2018}}<ref>{{cite news|last1=Breznican|first1=Anthony|title=Beauty and the Beast: Emma Watson addresses questions over Beast relationship|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/02/16/beauty-and-the-beast-emma-watson-belle-beast-relationship/|accessdate=March 26, 2017|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=February 16, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910210130/http://ew.com/movies/2017/02/16/beauty-and-the-beast-emma-watson-belle-beast-relationship/|archivedate=September 10, 2017}}</ref> Watson described Stockholm Syndrome as \"where a prisoner will take on the characteristics of and fall in love with the captor. Belle actively argues and disagrees with [Beast] constantly. She has none of the characteristics of someone with Stockholm Syndrome because she keeps her independence, she keeps that freedom of thought\", also adding that Belle defiantly \"gives as good as she gets\" before forming a friendship and romance with the Beast.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/02/16/beauty-and-the-beast-emma-watson-belle-beast-relationship/ |title=Beauty and the Beast: Emma Watson addresses questions over Beast relationship |accessdate=August 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910210130/http://ew.com/movies/2017/02/16/beauty-and-the-beast-emma-watson-belle-beast-relationship/ |archivedate=September 10, 2017  }}</ref>\n\nPsychiatrist [[Frank Ochberg]], who was responsible for defining the term \"Stockholm syndrome\", said he does not think Belle exhibits the trauma symptoms of prisoners suffering from the syndrome because she does not go through a period of feeling that she is going to die.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Watkins|first1=Gwynne|title=Does Belle From 'Beauty and the Beast' Suffer From Stockholm Syndrome? We Asked an Expert.|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/does-belle-from-beauty-and-the-beast-suffer-from-stockholm-syndrome-we-asked-an-expert-175449990.html|accessdate=March 26, 2017|publisher=Yahoo Movies|date=March 20, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910210202/https://www.yahoo.com/news/does-belle-from-beauty-and-the-beast-suffer-from-stockholm-syndrome-we-asked-an-expert-175449990.html|archivedate=September 10, 2017}}</ref> Some therapists, while acknowledging that the pairing's relationship does not meet the clinical definition of Stockholm syndrome, argue that the relationship depicted is dysfunctional and abusive and does not model healthy romantic relationships for young viewers.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Durvasula|first1=Ramani|title=Does Belle from Beauty and The Beast Have Stockholm Syndrome?|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5zyYzdsmeBU|accessdate=March 26, 2017|publisher=Screen Junkies|date=March 23, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407104600/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5zyYzdsmeBU|archivedate=April 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Simon|first1=Rachel|title=The 'Beauty and the Beast' Relationship Isn't \"Stockholm Syndrome,\" No Matter How Screwed Up It May Be|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/the-beauty-the-beast-relationship-isnt-stockholm-syndrome-no-matter-how-screwed-up-it-may-be-44217|accessdate=March 26, 2017|magazine=Bustle|date=March 16, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910210257/https://www.bustle.com/p/the-beauty-the-beast-relationship-isnt-stockholm-syndrome-no-matter-how-screwed-up-it-may-be-44217|archivedate=September 10, 2017}}</ref> Following this viewpoint, Constance Grady of [[Vox (website)|Vox]] wrote that [[Jeanne-Marie Leprince de Beaumont]]'s ''Beauty and the Beast'' was a fairy tale originally written to prepare young girls in 18th-century France for [[arranged marriage]]s, and that the power disparity is amplified in the Disney version.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Grady|first1=Constance|title=Is Beauty and the Beast \"a tale as old as Stockholm syndrome\"? Depends how you read it.|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2017/3/23/15000768/beauty-and-the-beast-feminist-stockholm-syndrome|accessdate=March 26, 2017|publisher=Vox|date=March 23, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910210439/https://www.vox.com/culture/2017/3/23/15000768/beauty-and-the-beast-feminist-stockholm-syndrome|archivedate=September 10, 2017}}</ref> Additionally, Anna Menta of ''[[Elite Daily]]'' argued that the Beast does not apologize to Belle for imprisoning, hurting, or manipulating her, and that his treatment of Belle is not painted as wrong.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Menta|first1=Anna|title=The 'Beauty and the Beast' Love Story Doesn't Hold Up To Emma Watson's Feminism|url=http://elitedaily.com/entertainment/film/beauty-and-the-beasts-abusive-relationship-emma-watson/1828119/|accessdate=March 26, 2017|website=Elite Daily|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910210528/http://elitedaily.com/entertainment/film/beauty-and-the-beasts-abusive-relationship-emma-watson/1828119/|archivedate=September 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Future==\n===Potential follow-up film===\nShortly after the release of the film, [[Sean Bailey]] said that [[Walt Disney Pictures]] will \"explore possible [live-action] spin-off and prequel scenarios\" for animated and live-action Disney films, including ''Beauty and the Beast''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/03/beauty-and-the-beast-sean-bailey-disney-emma-watson-1202047710/|title=Sean Bailey On How Disney's Live-Action Division Found Its 'Beauty and the Beast' Mojo|website=Deadline|date=March 21, 2017|first=Mike|last=Fleming Jr.|access-date=April 28, 2019|archive-url=https://archive.li/20170910100558/http://deadline.com/2017/03/beauty-and-the-beast-sean-bailey-disney-emma-watson-1202047710/|archive-date=September 10, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Both [[Dan Stevens]] and [[Emma Watson]] expressed interest in reprising their roles in potential sequel or prequel to the film.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/beauty-and-the-beast-sequel-dan-stevens-sex-comedy-permission-tribeca-1202393018/|title=Dan Stevens on 'Beauty and the Beast' Sequel Talk, Tribeca Sex Comedy 'Permission'|magazine=Variety|date=April 22, 2017|first=Ramin|last=Setoodeh|access-date=April 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430124608/https://variety.com/2017/film/news/beauty-and-the-beast-sequel-dan-stevens-sex-comedy-permission-tribeca-1202393018/|archive-date=April 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/1830510/emma-watson-brought-up-a-potential-beauty-and-the-beast-sequel-idea-again|title=Emma Watson Brought Up A Potential Beauty and the Beast Sequel Idea Again|website=Cinema Blend|date=January 9, 2018|first=Adam|last=Holmes|access-date=April 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190428043706/https://www.cinemablend.com/news/1830510/emma-watson-brought-up-a-potential-beauty-and-the-beast-sequel-idea-again|archive-date=April 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Spin-off/prequel series===\nOn March 6, 2020, it was reported that [[ABC Signature Studios]] is developing a prequel limited series to the film focused on Gaston and LeFou, for [[Disney+]].<ref name=\"Disney+Series\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/beauty-beast-prequel-series-works-at-disney-1282859|title='Beauty and the Beast' Prequel Series in the Works at Disney+ (Exclusive)|date=March 6, 2020|first=Lesley|last=Goldberg|access-date=March 7, 2020m|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Luke Evans]] and [[Josh Gad]] will reprise their roles from the film, and will executive-produce the series alongside [[Eddy Kitsis]] and [[Adam Horowitz]], with Gad, Kitsis and Horowitz serving as showrunners and writers for the series.<ref name=\"Disney+Series\"/> [[Alan Menken]] is in talks to return as composer for the series.<ref name=\"Disney+Series\"/>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{official website|http://movies.disney.com/beauty-and-the-beast-2017}}\n*{{IMDb title|2771200}}\n*{{Rotten Tomatoes|beauty_and_the_beast_2017|Beauty and the Beast}}\n*{{Box Office Mojo|beautyandthebeast2017}}\n*{{AllMovie title|601458}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=''Beauty and the Beast''|state=collapsed\n|list1=\n{{Beauty and the Beast}}\n{{Disney's Beauty and the Beast}}\n{{Disney Princess}}\n{{Disney's live-action adaptations of animated franchises}}\n{{Alan Menken|state=collapsed}}\n{{Howard Ashman|state=collapsed}}\n{{Tim Rice|state=collapsed}}\n{{Bill Condon}}\n{{Stephen Chbosky}}\n{{MTV Movie Award for Best Movie}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|Disney|Film|United States}}\n\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:2017 3D films]]\n[[Category:2010s musical fantasy films]]\n[[Category:2010s romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s romantic fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American 3D films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:American musical fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:American romantic fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:Beauty and the Beast (franchise)]]\n[[Category:Censored films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Disney film remakes]]\n[[Category:Films featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Films about curses]]\n[[Category:Films about royalty]]\n[[Category:Films about shapeshifting]]\n[[Category:Films based on adaptations]]\n[[Category:Films based on Beauty and the Beast]]\n[[Category:Films based on multiple works]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Linda Woolverton]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Alan Menken]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Bill Condon]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 18th century]]\n[[Category:Films set in castles]]\n[[Category:Films set in France]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Shepperton Studios]]\n[[Category:Films using computer-generated imagery]]\n[[Category:American historical romance films]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n[[Category:Mandeville Films films]]\n[[Category:Motion capture in film]]\n[[Category:Film remakes]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Evan Spiliotopoulos]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Stephen Chbosky]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Pictures films]]\n[[Category:American historical musical films]]\n", "name_user": "68.9.223.240", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beauty_and_the_Beast_(2017_film)"}
{"title_page": "Mariana Atencio", "text_new": "{{short description|Venezuelan journalist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Mariana Atencio\n| image           = Atencio Mariana.jpg\n| caption         =\n| birth_place     = [[Caracas]], [[Venezuela]]\n| birth_date      = 1984\n| death_date      =\n| death_place     =\n| othername       =\n| residence       =\n| nationality     = [[Venezuelan-American]]\n| occupation      = Journalist and Author\n| employer        =\n| education       = [[Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])<br>[[Universidad Cat\u00f3lica Andr\u00e9s Bello]], [[Caracas]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n| spouse          =\n| awards          = [[Peabody Award]], [[Investigative Reporters and Editors]] Award, [[Gracie Award]], [[National Association of Hispanic Journalists]] Presidential Award \n| website         = {{url|http://www.golikemariana.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Mariana Atencio''' (born 1984) is a bilingual journalist and author who was formerly a correspondent for [[MSNBC]] and [[NBC News]]. Atencio is a native of Venezuela and holds a master's degree from the [[Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism]]. She has also worked as an [[news presenter|anchor]] for [[Fusion TV]] and [[Univision]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nMariana del Carmen Atencio Cervoni was born in Caracas, Venezuela to Alvaro Atencio and Diana Cervoni. She is the oldest of three children.\n\nAtencio has a Bachelor's degree in Communications from the [[Universidad Cat\u00f3lica Andr\u00e9s Bello]] in Caracas.<ref name=\"univision bio\"/>\n\nAs a junior in college, she participated in the 2007 wave of pro-democracy student protests after former Venezuelan president [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]] shut down [[RCTV]], the country\u2019s oldest television network. She and her fellow students were tear-gassed and water cannons were opened on them. Atencio credits the protests as an influence to become a journalist.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://peopleenespanol.com/chica/mariana-atencio-talks-new-book/ |title=Journalist Mariana Atencio Details Personal Tragedy and Career Struggles in Inspirational New Memoir |publisher=People En Espa\u00f1ol |date=March 28, 2019 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref> Finally, she had to leave Venezuela because of multiple incidents of violence, including the murder of her \"high school sweetheart\".<ref name=\"Rejection\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/rejection-growth-journalist-mariana-atencio-shares-experiences-perfectly-you-n1021386 |title=From rejection to growth, journalist Mariana Atencio shares experiences in 'Perfectly You' |publisher=Nbcnews.com |date= |accessdate=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, she emigrated to the United States after being awarded the Castagno full-merit scholarship from [[Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism]], where she graduated with a master's degree.<ref name=\"univision bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.univision.com/noticias/univision-investiga/mariana-atencio|title=Mariana Atencio|publisher=Univision|date=27 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"People mag\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.peopleenespanol.com/article/periodista-mariana-atencio-comienza-nuevo-capitulo-boda-casa-Miami-feliz-univision|title=La periodista Mariana Atencio comienza un nuevo cap\u00edtulo en su vida (FOTOS)|newspaper=PeopleenEspanol.com|access-date=2016-11-19}}</ref> She has also studied at [[Georgetown University]], the [[London School of Economics]], and the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (UCLA).<ref name=\"univision bio\"/>\n\n==Career==\nIn 2009, Atencio started her journalism career as a reporter at Impremedia's ''El Diario''/''La Prensa'' in New York City, the oldest Hispanic newspaper in the US.<ref name=\"univision bio\"/> She has also worked as an anchor for the [[V-me|Vme-TV]] network, the only Hispanic public service television station in the United States.\n\n===Univision and Fusion (2011-2016)===\nAtencio began working as a guest anchor and correspondent for [[Univision]] News in 2011. She covered the 2012 presidential election for the network\u2019s morning program [[Despierta America]] and its flagship evening newscast [[Noticiero Univision]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://huelladigital.univisionnoticias.com/impacto-latino/mariana-atencio/index9ed2.html |title=Mariana Atencio |publisher=Univision Noticias |date= |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, she began working as an investigative reporter at [[Univision]].<ref name=\"univision bio\"/>  Atencio was one of five reporters who worked on the [[Peabody Award]] winning documentary Rapido y Furioso (Fast & Furious) for which they received an [[Investigative Reporters and Editors]] Award.<ref name=\"Abc\">{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/ABC_Univision/Politics/peabody-award-winning-univision-investigation-fast-furious/story?id=18840809#.UdTpceArjTQ |title=Behind the Peabody Award-Winning Univision Investigation of 'Fast and Furious\" - ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=2013-03-30 |accessdate=2013-09-02}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ire.org/publications/ire-journal/search-journal-archives/2206/ |format=PDF |title=IRE Award Winners: Spring 2013 |publisher=Investigative Reporters and Editors, Inc. |accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> She also served as a reporter for the network\u2019s Investigative Unit. In 2013 she was part of a five-person reporting team that won Univision's first [[Peabody Award]] for \"Fast and Furious: Arming the Enemy,\" an hour-long investigation on the gun-walking scandal known as [[Operation Fast and Furious]].<ref name=\"Abc\"/>\n\nIn 2014, Atencio received a [[Gracie Award]] from the [[Alliance for Women in Media]] for her work on the Univision documentary, \"Pressured: Freedom of the Press.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://wearefusion.tumblr.com/post/78142596070/fusions-mariana-atencio-recognized-with-gracie|title=Fusion\u2019s Mariana Atencio Recognized with Gracie Award|publisher=Fusion|date=28 February 2014}}</ref> Atencio received the National Association of Hispanic Journalists \u201cLatino Issues\u201d award.<ref name=\"Rejection\" />\n\nAtencio was a member of the anchor team for the network\u2019s ''The Morning Show'', a two-hour program featuring a mix of hard news, feature stories and live interviews. She anchored ''The Morning Show'' on [[Fusion TV]] channel until its cancellation in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mediamoves.com/2014/12/fusion-live-cancelled-javier-guzman-leaves-network.html|title=\"Fusion Live\" cancelled, Javier Guzm\u00e1n leaves network|date=2014-12-12|newspaper=Media Moves|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-27}}</ref> She was the reporter for Fusion's National Headliner Award-winning segment, \"Unearthing the Tomb.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://wearefusion.tumblr.com/post/142460895194/fusion-recognized-with-national-headliner-award|title=FUSION Recognized with National Headliner Award|website=FUSION}}</ref> Her report entitled, \u201cMexico Massacres,\u201d  received recognition from The National Association of Hispanic Journalists.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://wearefusion.tumblr.com/post/129569362744/fusion-recognized-with-3-nahj-journalism-awards/embed|title=Tumblr|website=wearefusion.tumblr.com}}</ref>\n\nShe also served as a field correspondent. Atencio led the network\u2019s on-the-ground coverage of the 2014 protests in Venezuela amid growing violence and scarcity, where she also contributed to ABC News.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/video/venezuelan-opposition-leader-leopoldo-lopezs-arrest-intensifies-protests-22589920 |title=Venezuelan Opposition Leader's Arrest Intensifies Protests |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/fusion-venezuela-abc-news-ukraine_n_4848861 |title=Fusion CEO Says Network\u2019s Partnerships Shone During International Coverage |publisher=Huffington Post |date=2014-02-24 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref> She has covered other notable stories such as the shooting [[death of Michael Brown]] in [[Ferguson, Missouri|Ferguson]], the [[Umbrella Revolution]] in Hong Kong, and the [[2014 Iguala mass kidnapping]], where 43 students went missing in Mexico.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://wearefusion.tumblr.com/post/129569362744/fusion-recognized-with-3-nahj-journalism-awards/embed |title=FUSION Recognized with 3 NAHJ Journalism Awards |publisher=Tumblr |date=2015 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, she was a reporter in [[McAllen, Texas]] for ABC News\u2019 virtual town hall with Pope Francis ahead of his first visit to the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://todayscatholic.org/pope-holds-virtual-town-hall-with-abc-and-catholics-in-3-cities/ |title=Pope holds 'virtual town hall' with ABC and Catholics in 3 cities |publisher=Today's Catholic |date=September 4, 2015 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref> She interacted with Pope Francis and translated on live television for recent immigrants who wanted to ask the pope questions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.emmys.com/news/mix/passion-and-purpose |title=Passion and Purpose |publisher=Emmys.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, she was part of the anchor-team for Univision and ''[[The Washington Post]]''\u2019s debate between Democratic candidates [[Hillary Clinton]] and [[Bernie Sanders]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.univision.com/noticias/destino-2016/univision-noticias-un-menu-digital-para-seguir-el-debate-democrata-de-miami |title=Univision Noticias: un men\u00fa digital para seguir el debate dem\u00f3crata de Miami |publisher=Univision |date=2016-03-09 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n===MSNBC and NBC News (2016-2020)===\nAtencio made the crossover from Spanish to English-language network news in September 2016 when she became a correspondent for MSNBC and NBC based in Miami. She was the only Latina correspondent on the cable network.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/viviannunez/2019/05/31/mariana-atencios-next-career-step-is-a-book-that-challenges-latinas-to-live-their-full-potential/#3cbb0ee51982 |title=Mariana Atencio's Next Career Step Is A Book That Challenges Latinas To Live Their Full Potential |publisher=Forbes |date=May 31, 2019 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nAs a correspondent, Atencio specialized in covering immigration and doing live on-air translations from Spanish.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.naludamagazine.com/mariana-atencio-interview/ |title=Interview with Award Winning TV Personality on Diversity & Activism Mariana Atencio |publisher=Naluda Magazine |date=February 27, 2019 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref> She reported on notable stories such as the [[Central American migrant caravans]], the child separation crisis at the border and the ICE raids across several Mississippi chicken plants that led to the arrest of 680 undocumented immigrants.\n\nAtencio\u2019s live interviews with migrant mothers in [[Reynosa]], Mexico during the Trump administration\u2019s family separation policy was nominated for a National [[Emmy Award]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cdn.emmyonline.org/news-doc-40th-emmys-nominations-v03.pdf |title=Nominees for the 40th Annual News & Document Emmy Awards |publisher=Emmyonline.org |date=July 25, 2019 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nShe also focused on coverage of U.S. Latinos. During the 2020 presidential race, the 2018 midterms and the 2016 presidential campaign, she reported on Hispanic voters across the country.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.msnbc.com/hallie-jackson/watch/suburban-detroit-voters-speak-on-key-election-issues-1363180611664 |title=Suburban Detroit voters speak on key election issues |publisher=MSNBC |date=Nov 6, 2018 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref> In 2019, she was part of a team of NBC and MSNBC reporters, known as \u201cRoad Warriors,\u201d that were awarded the First Amendment Clarity Award for their coverage of the 2018 midterm elections.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.firstamendmentawards.org/first-amendment-clarity-award-2019/ |title=First Amendment Clarity Award |publisher=firstamendmentawards.org |date=2018 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nAtencio covered major natural disasters including the earthquake in Mexico,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://peopleenespanol.com/chica/mariana-atencio-talks-new-book/ |title=Journalist Mariana Atencio Details Personal Tragedy and Career Struggles in Inspirational New Memoir |publisher=People En Espa\u00f1ol |date=March 28, 2019 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref> as well as the aftermath of Hurricanes [[Hurricane Maria|Maria]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/nightly-news/video/outside-san-juan-puerto-ricans-plea-for-supplies-1065214019728|title=Outside San Juan, Puerto Ricans plea for supplies (video)|date=7 October 2017}}</ref> [[Hurricane Harvey|Harvey]], [[Hurricane Florence|Florence]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://globalnews.ca/video/4450766/reporter-battered-by-hurricane-florence-as-she-walks-through-ghost-town-oak-island-nc |title=Reporter battered by Hurricane Florence as she walks through \u2018ghost town\u2019 Oak Island, NC |publisher=globalnews.ca |date=September 14, 2018 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref> [[Hurricane Michael|Michael]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.msnbc.com/katy-tur/watch/florida-cfo-on-hurricane-michael-recovery-1344776259697 |title=Florida CFO on Hurricane Michael recovery |publisher=MSNBC |date=Oct 16, 2018 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref> and [[Hurricane Dorian|Dorian]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.msnbc.com/velshi-ruhle/watch/a-harrowing-story-of-survival-from-hurricane-dorian-in-the-bahamas-68173381868 |title=A harrowing story of survival from Hurricane Dorian in the Bahamas |publisher=MSNBC |date=Sep 5, 2019 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nShe also co-founded GoLike in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://peopleenespanol.com/chica/mariana-atencio-launches-production-company/ |title=Mariana Atencio Leaves NBC News to Launch Her Own Media Empire |publisher=People En Espa\u00f1ol |date=January 3, 2020 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nOn June 11, 2019, [[Harper Collins]] published Atencio\u2019s first book ''Perfectly You: Embracing the Power of Being Real'', in English and Spanish. The book is self-help and part autobiography.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thomasnelson.com/p/perfectly-you/ |title=From MSNBC award-winning news journalist Mariana Atencio |publisher=Thomas Nelson |date= |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nOn the week of its release the book reached #1 on Amazon\u2019s Best Seller list for Hispanic & Latino Biographies and Christian Social Issues. Its audio counterpart was also named an Apple  \u201cMust-Listen\u201d  as well as an Audible Editor\u2019s Select in June 2019.\n\n==Personal life==\nAtencio lives between Miami and New York City.<ref name=\"Share 2019\">{{cite web | title=Award Winning Journalist Mariana Atencio | website=Diversity MBA Magazine | date=16 January 2019 | url=https://diversitymbamagazine.com/diversity-inclusion/hispanic-latino/award-winning-journalist-mariana-atencio/ | access-date=26 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nAtencio has written extensively about her sister Graciela Atencio. In 2014, Graciela was involved in a car accident in New York City. After multiple surgeries, she was able to regain her ability to walk. Mariana and her sister went on the air with the story to promote awareness for kids with disabilities.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.univision.com/especiales/teleton-usa/la-familia-de-mariana-atencio-vive-la-discapacidad-de-cerca-video |title=La familia de Mariana Atencio vive la \"discapacidad\" de cerca |publisher=Univision |date=December 4, 2015 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nAtencio\u2019s father passed away in February 2018 due to complications from pneumonia after contracting the flu. She chronicled his health crisis in the hospital in Caracas and the lack of basic medical supplies in Venezuela as a result of the humanitarian crisis.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/specials/venezuelas-health-crisis |title=In the chaos of Venezuela, a daughter fights for her father\u2019s life |publisher=NBC News |date=Apr 25, 2018 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://people.com/chica/mariana-atencios-father-dies-in-venezuelan-hospital-during-heathcare-crisis/ |title=MSNBC Journalist Mourns Father's Death and Sheds Light on Humanitarian Crisis in Venezuela |publisher=People |date=February 22, 2018 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book |last1=Atencio |first1=Mariana |title=Perfectly You: Embracing the Power of Being Real |date=2019 |publisher=W Publishing Group |isbn=9780785228387 |oclc=1080997518 |language=English}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|http://www.golikemariana.com/}}\n*[https://www.instagram.com/marianaatencio/ Instagram]\n*[https://twitter.com/marianaatencio Twitter]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/MarianaAtencio/ Facebook]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Atencio, Mariana}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:MSNBC people]]\n[[Category:Peabody Award winners]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan women journalists]]\n[[Category:American women journalists]]\n[[Category:American women television journalists]]\n[[Category:Women television journalists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Venezuelan journalist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Mariana Atencio\n| image           = Atencio Mariana.jpg\n| caption         =\n| birth_place     = [[Caracas]], [[Venezuela]]\n| birth_date      = 1984\n| death_date      =\n| death_place     =\n| othername       =\n| residence       =\n| nationality     = [[Venezuelan-American]]\n| occupation      = Journalist and Author\n| employer        =\n| education       = [[Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])<br>[[Universidad Cat\u00f3lica Andr\u00e9s Bello]], [[Caracas]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n| spouse          =\n| awards          = [[Peabody Award]], [[Investigative Reporters and Editors]] Award, [[Gracie Award]], [[National Association of Hispanic Journalists]] Presidential Award \n| website         = {{url|http://www.golikemariana.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Mariana Atencio''' (born 1984) is a bilingual journalist and author who was formerly a correspondent for [[MSNBC]] and [[NBC News]]. Atencio is a native of Venezuela and holds a master's degree from the [[Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism]]. She has also worked as an [[news presenter|anchor]] for [[Fusion TV]] and [[Univision]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nMariana del Carmen Atencio Cervoni was born in Caracas, Venezuela to Alvaro Atencio and Diana Cervoni. She is the oldest of three children.\n\nAtencio has a Bachelor's degree in Communications from the [[Universidad Cat\u00f3lica Andr\u00e9s Bello]] in Caracas.<ref name=\"univision bio\"/>\n\nAs a junior in college, she participated in the 2007 wave of pro-democracy student protests after former Venezuelan president [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]] shut down [[RCTV]], the country\u2019s oldest television network. She and her fellow students were tear-gassed and water cannons were opened on them. Atencio credits the protests as an influence to become a journalist.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://peopleenespanol.com/chica/mariana-atencio-talks-new-book/ |title=Journalist Mariana Atencio Details Personal Tragedy and Career Struggles in Inspirational New Memoir |publisher=People En Espa\u00f1ol |date=March 28, 2019 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref> Finally, she had to leave Venezuela because of multiple incidents of violence, including the murder of her \"high school sweetheart\".<ref name=\"Rejection\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/rejection-growth-journalist-mariana-atencio-shares-experiences-perfectly-you-n1021386 |title=From rejection to growth, journalist Mariana Atencio shares experiences in 'Perfectly You' |publisher=Nbcnews.com |date= |accessdate=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, she emigrated to the United States after being awarded the Castagno full-merit scholarship from [[Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism]], where she graduated with a master's degree.<ref name=\"univision bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.univision.com/noticias/univision-investiga/mariana-atencio|title=Mariana Atencio|publisher=Univision|date=27 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"People mag\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.peopleenespanol.com/article/periodista-mariana-atencio-comienza-nuevo-capitulo-boda-casa-Miami-feliz-univision|title=La periodista Mariana Atencio comienza un nuevo cap\u00edtulo en su vida (FOTOS)|newspaper=PeopleenEspanol.com|access-date=2016-11-19}}</ref> She has also studied at [[Georgetown University]], the [[London School of Economics]], and the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (UCLA).<ref name=\"univision bio\"/>\n\n==Career==\nIn 2009, Atencio started her journalism career as a reporter at Impremedia's ''El Diario''/''La Prensa'' in New York City, the oldest Hispanic newspaper in the US.<ref name=\"univision bio\"/> She has also worked as an anchor for the [[V-me|Vme-TV]] network, the only Hispanic public service television station in the United States.\n\n===Univision and Fusion (2011-2016)===\nAtencio began working as a guest anchor and correspondent for [[Univision]] News in 2011. She covered the 2012 presidential election for the network\u2019s morning program [[Despierta America]] and its flagship evening newscast [[Noticiero Univision]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://huelladigital.univisionnoticias.com/impacto-latino/mariana-atencio/index9ed2.html |title=Mariana Atencio |publisher=Univision Noticias |date= |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, she began working as an investigative reporter at [[Univision]].<ref name=\"univision bio\"/>  Atencio was one of five reporters who worked on the [[Peabody Award]] winning documentary Rapido y Furioso (Fast & Furious) for which they received an [[Investigative Reporters and Editors]] Award.<ref name=\"Abc\">{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/ABC_Univision/Politics/peabody-award-winning-univision-investigation-fast-furious/story?id=18840809#.UdTpceArjTQ |title=Behind the Peabody Award-Winning Univision Investigation of 'Fast and Furious\" - ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=2013-03-30 |accessdate=2013-09-02}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ire.org/publications/ire-journal/search-journal-archives/2206/ |format=PDF |title=IRE Award Winners: Spring 2013 |publisher=Investigative Reporters and Editors, Inc. |accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> She also served as a reporter for the network\u2019s Investigative Unit. In 2013 she was part of a five-person reporting team that won Univision's first [[Peabody Award]] for \"Fast and Furious: Arming the Enemy,\" an hour-long investigation on the gun-walking scandal known as [[Operation Fast and Furious]].<ref name=\"Abc\"/>\n\nIn 2014, Atencio received a [[Gracie Award]] from the [[Alliance for Women in Media]] for her work on the Univision documentary, \"Pressured: Freedom of the Press.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://wearefusion.tumblr.com/post/78142596070/fusions-mariana-atencio-recognized-with-gracie|title=Fusion\u2019s Mariana Atencio Recognized with Gracie Award|publisher=Fusion|date=28 February 2014}}</ref> Atencio received the National Association of Hispanic Journalists \u201cLatino Issues\u201d award.<ref name=\"Rejection\" />\n\nAtencio was a member of the anchor team for the network\u2019s ''The Morning Show'', a two-hour program featuring a mix of hard news, feature stories and live interviews. She anchored ''The Morning Show'' on [[Fusion TV]] channel until its cancellation in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mediamoves.com/2014/12/fusion-live-cancelled-javier-guzman-leaves-network.html|title=\"Fusion Live\" cancelled, Javier Guzm\u00e1n leaves network|date=2014-12-12|newspaper=Media Moves|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-27}}</ref> She was the reporter for Fusion's National Headliner Award-winning segment, \"Unearthing the Tomb.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://wearefusion.tumblr.com/post/142460895194/fusion-recognized-with-national-headliner-award|title=FUSION Recognized with National Headliner Award|website=FUSION}}</ref> Her report entitled, \u201cMexico Massacres,\u201d  received recognition from The National Association of Hispanic Journalists.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://wearefusion.tumblr.com/post/129569362744/fusion-recognized-with-3-nahj-journalism-awards/embed|title=Tumblr|website=wearefusion.tumblr.com}}</ref>\n\nShe also served as a field correspondent. Atencio led the network\u2019s on-the-ground coverage of the 2014 protests in Venezuela amid growing violence and scarcity, where she also contributed to ABC News.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/video/venezuelan-opposition-leader-leopoldo-lopezs-arrest-intensifies-protests-22589920 |title=Venezuelan Opposition Leader's Arrest Intensifies Protests |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/fusion-venezuela-abc-news-ukraine_n_4848861 |title=Fusion CEO Says Network\u2019s Partnerships Shone During International Coverage |publisher=Huffington Post |date=2014-02-24 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref> She has covered other notable stories such as the shooting [[death of Michael Brown]] in [[Ferguson, Missouri|Ferguson]], the [[Umbrella Revolution]] in Hong Kong, and the [[2014 Iguala mass kidnapping]], where 43 students went missing in Mexico.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://wearefusion.tumblr.com/post/129569362744/fusion-recognized-with-3-nahj-journalism-awards/embed |title=FUSION Recognized with 3 NAHJ Journalism Awards |publisher=Tumblr |date=2015 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, she was a reporter in McAllen, Texas for ABC News\u2019 virtual town hall with Pope Francis ahead of his first visit to the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://todayscatholic.org/pope-holds-virtual-town-hall-with-abc-and-catholics-in-3-cities/ |title=Pope holds 'virtual town hall' with ABC and Catholics in 3 cities |publisher=Today's Catholic |date=September 4, 2015 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref> She interacted with Pope Francis and translated on live television for recent immigrants who wanted to ask the pope questions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.emmys.com/news/mix/passion-and-purpose |title=Passion and Purpose |publisher=Emmys.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, she was part of the anchor-team for Univision and ''[[The Washington Post]]''\u2019s debate between Democratic candidates [[Hillary Clinton]] and [[Bernie Sanders]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.univision.com/noticias/destino-2016/univision-noticias-un-menu-digital-para-seguir-el-debate-democrata-de-miami |title=Univision Noticias: un men\u00fa digital para seguir el debate dem\u00f3crata de Miami |publisher=Univision |date=2016-03-09 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n===MSNBC and NBC News (2016-2020)===\nAtencio made the crossover from Spanish to English-language network news in September 2016 when she became a correspondent for MSNBC and NBC based in Miami. She was the only Latina correspondent on the cable network.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/viviannunez/2019/05/31/mariana-atencios-next-career-step-is-a-book-that-challenges-latinas-to-live-their-full-potential/#3cbb0ee51982 |title=Mariana Atencio's Next Career Step Is A Book That Challenges Latinas To Live Their Full Potential |publisher=Forbes |date=May 31, 2019 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nAs a correspondent, Atencio specialized in covering immigration and doing live on-air translations from Spanish.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.naludamagazine.com/mariana-atencio-interview/ |title=Interview with Award Winning TV Personality on Diversity & Activism Mariana Atencio |publisher=Naluda Magazine |date=February 27, 2019 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref> She reported on notable stories such as the [[Central American migrant caravans]], the child separation crisis at the border and the ICE raids across several Mississippi chicken plants that led to the arrest of 680 undocumented immigrants.\n\nAtencio\u2019s live interviews with migrant mothers in [[Reynosa]], Mexico during the Trump administration\u2019s family separation policy was nominated for a National [[Emmy Award]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cdn.emmyonline.org/news-doc-40th-emmys-nominations-v03.pdf |title=Nominees for the 40th Annual News & Document Emmy Awards |publisher=Emmyonline.org |date=July 25, 2019 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nShe also focused on coverage of U.S. Latinos. During the 2020 presidential race, the 2018 midterms and the 2016 presidential campaign, she reported on Hispanic voters across the country.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.msnbc.com/hallie-jackson/watch/suburban-detroit-voters-speak-on-key-election-issues-1363180611664 |title=Suburban Detroit voters speak on key election issues |publisher=MSNBC |date=Nov 6, 2018 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref> In 2019, she was part of a team of NBC and MSNBC reporters, known as \u201cRoad Warriors,\u201d that were awarded the First Amendment Clarity Award for their coverage of the 2018 midterm elections.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.firstamendmentawards.org/first-amendment-clarity-award-2019/ |title=First Amendment Clarity Award |publisher=firstamendmentawards.org |date=2018 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nAtencio covered major natural disasters including the earthquake in Mexico,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://peopleenespanol.com/chica/mariana-atencio-talks-new-book/ |title=Journalist Mariana Atencio Details Personal Tragedy and Career Struggles in Inspirational New Memoir |publisher=People En Espa\u00f1ol |date=March 28, 2019 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref> as well as the aftermath of Hurricanes [[Hurricane Maria|Maria]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/nightly-news/video/outside-san-juan-puerto-ricans-plea-for-supplies-1065214019728|title=Outside San Juan, Puerto Ricans plea for supplies (video)|date=7 October 2017}}</ref> [[Hurricane Harvey|Harvey]], [[Hurricane Florence|Florence]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://globalnews.ca/video/4450766/reporter-battered-by-hurricane-florence-as-she-walks-through-ghost-town-oak-island-nc |title=Reporter battered by Hurricane Florence as she walks through \u2018ghost town\u2019 Oak Island, NC |publisher=globalnews.ca |date=September 14, 2018 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref> [[Hurricane Michael|Michael]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.msnbc.com/katy-tur/watch/florida-cfo-on-hurricane-michael-recovery-1344776259697 |title=Florida CFO on Hurricane Michael recovery |publisher=MSNBC |date=Oct 16, 2018 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref> and [[Hurricane Dorian|Dorian]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.msnbc.com/velshi-ruhle/watch/a-harrowing-story-of-survival-from-hurricane-dorian-in-the-bahamas-68173381868 |title=A harrowing story of survival from Hurricane Dorian in the Bahamas |publisher=MSNBC |date=Sep 5, 2019 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nShe also co-founded GoLike in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://peopleenespanol.com/chica/mariana-atencio-launches-production-company/ |title=Mariana Atencio Leaves NBC News to Launch Her Own Media Empire |publisher=People En Espa\u00f1ol |date=January 3, 2020 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nOn June 11, 2019, [[Harper Collins]] published Atencio\u2019s first book ''Perfectly You: Embracing the Power of Being Real'', in English and Spanish. The book is self-help and part autobiography.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thomasnelson.com/p/perfectly-you/ |title=From MSNBC award-winning news journalist Mariana Atencio |publisher=Thomas Nelson |date= |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nOn the week of its release the book reached #1 on Amazon\u2019s Best Seller list for Hispanic & Latino Biographies and Christian Social Issues. Its audio counterpart was also named an Apple  \u201cMust-Listen\u201d  as well as an Audible Editor\u2019s Select in June 2019.\n\n==Personal life==\nAtencio lives between Miami and New York City.<ref name=\"Share 2019\">{{cite web | title=Award Winning Journalist Mariana Atencio | website=Diversity MBA Magazine | date=16 January 2019 | url=https://diversitymbamagazine.com/diversity-inclusion/hispanic-latino/award-winning-journalist-mariana-atencio/ | access-date=26 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nAtencio has written extensively about her sister Graciela Atencio. In 2014, Graciela was involved in a car accident in New York City. After multiple surgeries, she was able to regain her ability to walk. Mariana and her sister went on the air with the story to promote awareness for kids with disabilities.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.univision.com/especiales/teleton-usa/la-familia-de-mariana-atencio-vive-la-discapacidad-de-cerca-video |title=La familia de Mariana Atencio vive la \"discapacidad\" de cerca |publisher=Univision |date=December 4, 2015 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nAtencio\u2019s father passed away in February 2018 due to complications from pneumonia after contracting the flu. She chronicled his health crisis in the hospital in Caracas and the lack of basic medical supplies in Venezuela as a result of the humanitarian crisis.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/specials/venezuelas-health-crisis |title=In the chaos of Venezuela, a daughter fights for her father\u2019s life |publisher=NBC News |date=Apr 25, 2018 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://people.com/chica/mariana-atencios-father-dies-in-venezuelan-hospital-during-heathcare-crisis/ |title=MSNBC Journalist Mourns Father's Death and Sheds Light on Humanitarian Crisis in Venezuela |publisher=People |date=February 22, 2018 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book |last1=Atencio |first1=Mariana |title=Perfectly You: Embracing the Power of Being Real |date=2019 |publisher=W Publishing Group |isbn=9780785228387 |oclc=1080997518 |language=English}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|http://www.golikemariana.com/}}\n*[https://www.instagram.com/marianaatencio/ Instagram]\n*[https://twitter.com/marianaatencio Twitter]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/MarianaAtencio/ Facebook]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Atencio, Mariana}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:MSNBC people]]\n[[Category:Peabody Award winners]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan women journalists]]\n[[Category:American women journalists]]\n[[Category:American women television journalists]]\n[[Category:Women television journalists]]\n", "name_user": "PalabrasLogos", "label": "safe", "comment": "in McAllen", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mariana_Atencio"}
{"title_page": "Robert Bridges", "text_new": "{{for|the American critic, editor and writer|Robert Bridges (critic)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Robert Bridges\n| image        = Robert Bridges.jpg\n| imagesize    = 210px\n| office        = [[Poet Laureate of the United Kingdom]]\n| monarch            = [[George V]]\n| term_start         = 25 July 1913\n| term_end           = 21 April 1930\n| predecessor        = [[Alfred Austin]]\n| successor          = [[John Masefield]]\n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| pseudonym    = \n| birth_name    =Robert Seymour Bridges\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1844|10|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Walmer]], [[Kent]], England\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1930|04|21|1844|10|23|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Boars Hill]], [[Berkshire]], England\n| occupation   = Writer\n| nationality  = British\n| citizenship  = \n| education    = \n| alma_mater   = [[Corpus Christi College, Oxford]]<br>[[St Bartholomew's Hospital]]\n| period       = \n| genre        = Poetry\n| subject      = \n| movement     = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse       = \n| partner      = \n| children     = \n| relatives    = \n| influences   = \n| influenced   = \n| awards       = Poet Laureate\n| signature    = \n| website      = \n| portaldisp   = \n}}\n\n'''Robert Seymour Bridges''' {{Postnominals|country=UK|OM}} (23 October 1844 &ndash; 21 April 1930) was Britain's [[poet laureate]] from 1913 to 1930. A doctor by training, he achieved literary fame only late in life. His poems reflect a deep Christian faith, and he is the author of many well-known hymns. It was through Bridges\u2019 efforts that [[Gerard Manley Hopkins]] achieved posthumous fame.\n\n==Personal and professional life==\n{{Quote box |width=300px |align=left |quoted=true |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |salign=right\n |quote  =<poem>\n\"'''The Evening Darkens Over'''\"\n\nThe evening darkens over \nAfter a day so bright, \nThe windcapt waves discover \nThat wild will be the night. \nThere's sound of distant thunder.\n\nThe latest sea-birds hover \nAlong the cliff's sheer height; \nAs in the memory wander \nLast flutterings of delight, \nWhite wings lost on the white.\n\nThere's not a ship in sight; \nAnd as the sun goes under, \nThick clouds conspire to cover \nThe moon that should rise yonder. \nThou art alone, fond lover.\n</poem>}}\nBridges was born at [[Walmer]], [[Kent]], in [[England]], the son of John Thomas Bridges (died 1853) and his wife Harriett Elizabeth, daughter of the Rev. [[Sir Robert Affleck, 4th Baronet]]. He was the fourth son and eighth child. After his father's death his mother married again, in 1854, to [[John Edward Nassau Molesworth]], vicar of [[Rochdale]], and the family moved there.<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=32066|first=Catherine|last=Phillips|title=Bridges, Robert Seymour}}</ref>\n\nBridges was educated at [[Eton College]] and [[Corpus Christi College, Oxford]].<ref>[http://www.englishverse.com/poets/bridges_robert Bridges, Robert]</ref> He went on to study medicine in London at [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]], intending to practise until the age of forty and then retire to write poetry. He practised as a casualty physician at his teaching hospital (where he made a series of highly critical remarks abothe Victorian medical establishment) and subsequently as a full physician to the Great (later Royal) Northern Hospital. He was also a physician to the Hospital for Sick Children.\n\nLung disease forced Bridges to retire in 1882, and from that point on he devoted himself to writing and literary research. However, Bridges' literary work started long before his retirement, his first collection of poems having been published in 1873. In 1884 he married Mary Monica Waterhouse, daughter of the architect [[Alfred Waterhouse]] [[Royal Academy|R.A.]], and spent the rest of his life in rural seclusion, first at [[Yattendon]], then at [[Boars Hill]], [[Berkshire]], where he died.\n\nHe was elected to the Fellowship of the Royal College of Physicians of London in 1900. He was appointed Poet Laureate in 1913, the only medical graduate to have held the office.\n\nHe was the father of poet [[Elizabeth Daryush]] and of the cabinet secretary [[Edward Bridges, 1st Baron Bridges|Edward Bridges]].\n[[File:Memorial to Robert Bridges and Edward Bridges, 1st Baron Bridges, in St Nicholas-at-Wade.jpg|thumb|Memorial to Robert Bridges and Edward Bridges, 1st Baron Bridges, in [[St Nicholas-at-Wade]], Kent]]\n\n==Literary work==\nAs a poet Bridges stands rather apart from the current of modern English verse, but his work has had great influence in a select circle, by its restraint, purity, precision and delicacy yet strength of expression. It embodies a distinct theory of [[Meter (poetry)|prosody]]. Bridges' faith underpinned much of his work.<ref>Collins A S, ''English Literature of the Twentieth Century'', University Tutorial Press, London, 1951.</ref>\n\nIn the book ''[[Milton's Prosody (book)|Milton's Prosody]]'', he took an empirical approach to examining Milton's use of [[blank verse]], and developed the controversial theory that Milton's practice was essentially [[Syllabic verse|syllabic]]. He considered [[free verse]] to be too limiting, and explained his position in the essay \"[[Humdrum and Harum-Scarum]]\". His own efforts to \"free\" verse resulted in the poems he called \"[[Neo-Miltonic Syllabics]]\", which were collected in ''New Verse'' (1925). The [[Meter (poetry)|metre]] of these poems was based on syllables rather than accents, and he used the principle again in the long philosophical poem ''The Testament of Beauty'' (1929), for which he was appointed to the [[Order of Merit]] in that year.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=14553 |date=4 June 1929 |page=567 |city=Edinburgh}}</ref> His best-known poems, however, are to be found in the two earlier volumes of ''Shorter Poems'' (1890, 1894). He also wrote verse plays, with limited success, and [[literary criticism]], including a study of the work of [[John Keats]].\n{{Quote box |width=300px |align=right |quoted=true |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |salign=right\n |quote  =<poem>\n'''\"Melancholia\"'''\nThe sickness of desire, that in dark days \nLooks on the imagination of despair, \nForgetteth man, and stinteth God his praise; \nNor but in sleep findeth a cure for care. \nIncertainty that once gave scope to dream \nOf laughing enterprise and glory untold, \nIs now a blackness that no stars redeem, \nA wall of terror in a night of cold.\n\nFool! thou that hast impossibly desired \nAnd now impatiently despairest, see \nHow nought is changed: Joy's wisdom is attired \nSplended for others' eyes if not for thee: \nNot love or beauty or youth from earth is fled: \nIf they delite thee not, 'tis thou art dead.\n</poem>}}\nBridges' poetry was privately printed in the first instance, and was slow in making its way beyond a comparatively small circle of his admirers. His best work is to be found in his ''Shorter Poems'' (1890), and a complete edition (to date) of his ''Poetical Works'' (6 vols.) was published in 1898\u20131905.\n\nDespite being made poet laureate in 1913, Bridges was never a very well-known poet and only achieved his great popularity shortly before his death with ''The Testament of Beauty''. However, his verse evoked response in many great British composers of the time. Among those to set his poems to music were [[Hubert Parry]], [[Gustav Holst]] and later [[Gerald Finzi]].<ref>Gerald Finzi, ''Seven Poems of Robert Bridges for mixed voices'' a capella, Boosey and Hawkes, 1939</ref>\n\nDuring the [[First World War]], Bridges joined the group of writers assembled by [[Charles Masterman]] as part of Britain's War Propaganda Bureau at [[Wellington House]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Marlin|first1=Randal|title=Propaganda and the Ethics of Persuasion|date=2002|publisher=Broadview Press|page=91|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Zp38Ot2g7LEC&dq=wellington+house+robert+bridges|accessdate=24 April 2016|isbn=9781551113760}}</ref>\n\nAt Oxford, Bridges befriended [[Gerard Manley Hopkins]], who is now considered a superior poet but who owes his present fame to Bridges' efforts in arranging the posthumous publication (1918) of his verse.\n\nBridges received advice from the young phonetician [[David Abercrombie (linguist)|David Abercrombie]] on the reformed spelling system he was devising for the publication of his collected essays (later published in seven volumes by [[Oxford University Press]], with the help of the distinguished typographer [[Stanley Morison]], who designed the new letters). Thus Robert Bridges contributed to phonetics and he was also a founder member of the Society for Pure English.<ref>Horsley E M, ''Hutchinson's New Twentieth Century Encyclopedia'', London 1964</ref>\n\n===Hymnody===\nBridges made an important contribution to hymnody with the publication in 1899 of his ''[[Yattendon Hymnal]]'', which he created specifically for musical reasons. This collection of hymns, although not a financial success, became a bridge between the Victorian hymnody of the last half of the 19th century and the modern hymnody of the early 20th century.\n \nBridges wrote and also translated historic hymns, and many of these were included in ''[[Songs of Syon]]'' (1904) and the later [[English Hymnal]] (1906). Several of Bridges' hymns and translations are still in use today:\n\n*\"Thee will I love, my God and King\"\n*\"Happy are they that love God\"\n*\"Rejoice, O land, in God thy might\"\n**The Baptist Hymn Book, University Press, Oxford 1962\n*\"Ah, Holy Jesus\" ([[Johann Heermann]], 1630)\n*\"[[All My Hope on God is Founded|All my hope on God is founded]]\" ([[Joachim Neander]], c. 1680)\n*\"[[Jesu, Joy of Man's Desiring]]\" (Martin Jahn, 1661)\n*\"O Gladsome Light\" ([[Phos Hilaron]])\n*\"O Sacred Head, sore wounded\" (Paulus Gerhardt, 1656)\n*\"O Splendour of God's Glory Bright\" (Ambrose, 4th century)\n*\"When morning gilds the skies\" (stanza 3; Katholisches Gesangbuch, 1744)\n\n==Major works==\nDates given are of first publication and significant revisions.\n\n===Poetry collections===\n*The Growth of Love (1876; 1889; 1898), a sequence of (24; 79; 69) sonnets\n*Prometheus the Firegiver: A Mask in the Greek Manner (1883)\n*[[Eros and Psyche (Robert Bridges)|Eros and Psyche: A Narrative Poem in Twelve Measures]] (1885; 1894), a story from the Latin of Apuleius\n*Shorter Poems, Books I\u2013IV (1890)\n*Shorter Poems, Books I\u2013V (1894)\n*New Poems (1899)\n*Demeter: A Mask (1905), performed in 1904 at the opening of the [[Somerville College Library]]\n*Ibant Obscuri: An Experiment in the Classical Hexameter (1916), with reprint of summary of Stone's Prosody, accompanied by 'later observations & modifications'\n*October and Other Poems (1920)\n*The Tapestry: Poems (1925), in [[neo-Miltonic syllabics]]\n*New Verse (1926), includes verse of ''The Tapestry''\n*The Testament of Beauty (1929)\n\n===Verse drama===\n*Nero (1885), an historical tragedy; called ''The First Part of Nero'' subsequent to the publication of ''Nero: Part II''\n*The Feast of Bacchus (1889); partly translated from the ''Heauton-Timoroumenos'' of [[Terence]]\n*Achilles in Scyros (1890), a drama in a mixed manner\n*Palicio (1890), a romantic drama in five acts in the Elizabethan manner\n*The Return of Ulysses (1890), a drama in five acts in a mixed manner\n*The Christian Captives (1890), a tragedy in five acts in a mixed manner; on the same subject as [[Pedro Calder\u00f3n de la Barca|Calder\u00f3n]]'s ''El Principe Constante''\n*The Humours of the Court (1893), a comedy in three acts; founded on Calder\u00f3n's ''El secreto \u00e1 voces'' and on [[Lope de Vega]]'s ''El Perro del hortelano''\n*Nero, Part II (1894)\n\n===Prose===\n*[[Milton's Prosody (book)|Milton's Prosody, With a Chapter on Accentual Verse]] (1893; 1901; 1921), based on essays published in 1887 and 1889\n*Keats (1895)\n*Hymns from the Yattendon Hymnal (1899)\n*The Spirit of Man (1916)\n*Poems of Gerard Manley Hopkins (1918), edited with notes by R.B.\n*The Necessity of Poetry (1918)\n*Collected Essays, Papers, Etc. (1927\u201336)\n\n==See also==\n*[[Robert Bridges' theory of elision]]\n*[[Bridges' analysis of Milton's later work]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* Bridges, Robert: ''The Poetical Works of Robert Bridges'', Oxford Editions of Standard Authors, Oxford University Press, 2nd edition, 1936. (reissued 1953 with ''The Testament of Beauty'')\n* Gu\u00e9rard, Albert, Jr.: ''Robert Bridges: A Study of Traditionalism in Poetry'', Harvard University Press, 1942.\n* Phillips, Catherine: ''Robert Bridges: A Biography'', Oxford University Press, 1992.  {{ISBN|0-19-212251-7}}\n* Stanford, Donald E.: ''In the Classic Mode: The Achievement of Robert Bridges'', Associated University Presses, 1978. {{ISBN|0-87413-118-9}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{wikisource-author}}\n* {{Gutenberg author |id=5418}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Robert Seymour Bridges}}\n* {{Librivox author |id=277}}\n* [http://www.poetsgraves.co.uk/bridges.htm Robert Bridges' Grave]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=British [[Poet Laureate]]|before=[[Alfred Austin]]|after=[[John Masefield]]|years=1913&ndash;1930}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Poets Laureate of the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bridges, Robert}}\n[[Category:1844 births]]\n[[Category:1930 deaths]]\n[[Category:English Anglicans]]\n[[Category:British Poets Laureate]]\n[[Category:People from Walmer]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Corpus Christi College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Medical College of St Bartholomew's Hospital]]\n[[Category:19th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:Victorian poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century English poets]]\n[[Category:People from Yattendon]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the American critic, editor and writer|Robert Bridges (critic)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Robert Bridges\n| image        = Robert Bridges.jpg\n| imagesize    = 210px\n| office        = [[Poet Laureate of the United Kingdom]]\n| monarch            = [[George V]]\n| term_start         = 25 July 1913\n| term_end           = 21 April 1930\n| predecessor        = [[Alfred Austin]]\n| successor          = [[John Masefield]]\n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| pseudonym    = \n| birth_name    =Robert Seymour Bridges\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1844|10|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Walmer]], [[Kent]], England\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1930|04|21|1844|10|23|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Boars Hill]], [[Berkshire]], England\n| occupation   = Writer\n| nationality  = British\n| citizenship  = \n| education    = \n| alma_mater   = [[Corpus Christi College, Oxford]]<br>[[St Bartholomew's Hospital]]\n| period       = \n| genre        = Poetry\n| subject      = \n| movement     = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse       = \n| partner      = \n| children     = \n| relatives    = \n| influences   = \n| influenced   = \n| awards       = Poet Laureate\n| signature    = \n| website      = \n| portaldisp   = \n}}\n\n'''Robert Seymour Bridges''' {{Postnominals|country=UK|OM}} (23 October 1844 &ndash; 21 April 1930) was Britain's [[poet laureate]] from 1913 to 1930. A doctor by training, he achieved literary fame only late in life. His poems reflect a deep Christian faith, and he is the author of many well-known hymns. It was through Bridges\u2019 efforts that [[Gerard Manley Hopkins]] achieved posthumous fame.\n\n==Personal and professional life==\n{{Quote box |width=300px |align=left |quoted=true |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |salign=right\n |quote  =<poem>\n\"'''The Evening Darkens Over'''\"\n\nThe evening darkens over \nAfter a day so bright, \nThe windcapt waves discover \nThat wild will be the night. \nThere's sound of distant thunder.\n\nThe latest sea-birds hover \nAlong the cliff's sheer height; \nAs in the memory wander \nLast flutterings of delight, \nWhite wings lost on the white.\n\nThere's not a ship in sight; \nAnd as the sun goes under, \nThick clouds conspire to cover \nThe moon that should rise yonder. \nThou art alone, fond lover.\n</poem>}}\nBridges was born at [[Walmer]], [[Kent]], in [[England]], the son of John Thomas Bridges (died 1853) and his wife Harriett Elizabeth, daughter of the Rev. [[Sir Robert Affleck, 4th Baronet]]. He was the fourth son and eighth child. After his father's death his mother married again, in 1854, to [[John Edward Nassau Molesworth]], vicar of [[Rochdale]], and the family moved there.<ref name=\"DNB\"/><ref name=\"ODNB\">{{cite ODNB|id=18899|first=Ellie|last=Clewlow|title=Molesworth, John Edward Nassau}}</ref><ref>{{cite ODNB|id=32066|first=Catherine|last=Phillips|title=Bridges, Robert Seymour}}</ref>\n\nBridges was educated at [[Eton College]] and [[Corpus Christi College, Oxford]].<ref>[http://www.englishverse.com/poets/bridges_robert Bridges, Robert]</ref> He went on to study medicine in London at [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]], intending to practise until the age of forty and then retire to write poetry. He practised as a casualty physician at his teaching hospital (where he made a series of highly critical remarks abothe Victorian medical establishment) and subsequently as a full physician to the Great (later Royal) Northern Hospital. He was also a physician to the Hospital for Sick Children.\n\nLung disease forced Bridges to retire in 1882, and from that point on he devoted himself to writing and literary research. However, Bridges' literary work started long before his retirement, his first collection of poems having been published in 1873. In 1884 he married Mary Monica Waterhouse, daughter of the architect [[Alfred Waterhouse]] [[Royal Academy|R.A.]], and spent the rest of his life in rural seclusion, first at [[Yattendon]], then at [[Boars Hill]], [[Berkshire]], where he died.\n\nHe was elected to the Fellowship of the Royal College of Physicians of London in 1900. He was appointed Poet Laureate in 1913, the only medical graduate to have held the office.\n\nHe was the father of poet [[Elizabeth Daryush]] and of the cabinet secretary [[Edward Bridges, 1st Baron Bridges|Edward Bridges]].\n[[File:Memorial to Robert Bridges and Edward Bridges, 1st Baron Bridges, in St Nicholas-at-Wade.jpg|thumb|Memorial to Robert Bridges and Edward Bridges, 1st Baron Bridges, in [[St Nicholas-at-Wade]], Kent]]\n\n==Literary work==\nAs a poet Bridges stands rather apart from the current of modern English verse, but his work has had great influence in a select circle, by its restraint, purity, precision and delicacy yet strength of expression. It embodies a distinct theory of [[Meter (poetry)|prosody]]. Bridges' faith underpinned much of his work.<ref>Collins A S, ''English Literature of the Twentieth Century'', University Tutorial Press, London, 1951.</ref>\n\nIn the book ''[[Milton's Prosody (book)|Milton's Prosody]]'', he took an empirical approach to examining Milton's use of [[blank verse]], and developed the controversial theory that Milton's practice was essentially [[Syllabic verse|syllabic]]. He considered [[free verse]] to be too limiting, and explained his position in the essay \"[[Humdrum and Harum-Scarum]]\". His own efforts to \"free\" verse resulted in the poems he called \"[[Neo-Miltonic Syllabics]]\", which were collected in ''New Verse'' (1925). The [[Meter (poetry)|metre]] of these poems was based on syllables rather than accents, and he used the principle again in the long philosophical poem ''The Testament of Beauty'' (1929), for which he was appointed to the [[Order of Merit]] in that year.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=14553 |date=4 June 1929 |page=567 |city=Edinburgh}}</ref> His best-known poems, however, are to be found in the two earlier volumes of ''Shorter Poems'' (1890, 1894). He also wrote verse plays, with limited success, and [[literary criticism]], including a study of the work of [[John Keats]].\n{{Quote box |width=300px |align=right |quoted=true |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |salign=right\n |quote  =<poem>\n'''\"Melancholia\"'''\nThe sickness of desire, that in dark days \nLooks on the imagination of despair, \nForgetteth man, and stinteth God his praise; \nNor but in sleep findeth a cure for care. \nIncertainty that once gave scope to dream \nOf laughing enterprise and glory untold, \nIs now a blackness that no stars redeem, \nA wall of terror in a night of cold.\n\nFool! thou that hast impossibly desired \nAnd now impatiently despairest, see \nHow nought is changed: Joy's wisdom is attired \nSplended for others' eyes if not for thee: \nNot love or beauty or youth from earth is fled: \nIf they delite thee not, 'tis thou art dead.\n</poem>}}\nBridges' poetry was privately printed in the first instance, and was slow in making its way beyond a comparatively small circle of his admirers. His best work is to be found in his ''Shorter Poems'' (1890), and a complete edition (to date) of his ''Poetical Works'' (6 vols.) was published in 1898\u20131905.\n\nDespite being made poet laureate in 1913, Bridges was never a very well-known poet and only achieved his great popularity shortly before his death with ''The Testament of Beauty''. However, his verse evoked response in many great British composers of the time. Among those to set his poems to music were [[Hubert Parry]], [[Gustav Holst]] and later [[Gerald Finzi]].<ref>Gerald Finzi, ''Seven Poems of Robert Bridges for mixed voices'' a capella, Boosey and Hawkes, 1939</ref>\n\nDuring the [[First World War]], Bridges joined the group of writers assembled by [[Charles Masterman]] as part of Britain's War Propaganda Bureau at [[Wellington House]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Marlin|first1=Randal|title=Propaganda and the Ethics of Persuasion|date=2002|publisher=Broadview Press|page=91|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Zp38Ot2g7LEC&dq=wellington+house+robert+bridges|accessdate=24 April 2016|isbn=9781551113760}}</ref>\n\nAt Oxford, Bridges befriended [[Gerard Manley Hopkins]], who is now considered a superior poet but who owes his present fame to Bridges' efforts in arranging the posthumous publication (1918) of his verse.\n\nBridges received advice from the young phonetician [[David Abercrombie (linguist)|David Abercrombie]] on the reformed spelling system he was devising for the publication of his collected essays (later published in seven volumes by [[Oxford University Press]], with the help of the distinguished typographer [[Stanley Morison]], who designed the new letters). Thus Robert Bridges contributed to phonetics and he was also a founder member of the Society for Pure English.<ref>Horsley E M, ''Hutchinson's New Twentieth Century Encyclopedia'', London 1964</ref>\n\n===Hymnody===\nBridges made an important contribution to hymnody with the publication in 1899 of his ''[[Yattendon Hymnal]]'', which he created specifically for musical reasons. This collection of hymns, although not a financial success, became a bridge between the Victorian hymnody of the last half of the 19th century and the modern hymnody of the early 20th century.\n \nBridges wrote and also translated historic hymns, and many of these were included in ''[[Songs of Syon]]'' (1904) and the later [[English Hymnal]] (1906). Several of Bridges' hymns and translations are still in use today:\n\n*\"Thee will I love, my God and King\"\n*\"Happy are they that love God\"\n*\"Rejoice, O land, in God thy might\"\n**The Baptist Hymn Book, University Press, Oxford 1962\n*\"Ah, Holy Jesus\" ([[Johann Heermann]], 1630)\n*\"[[All My Hope on God is Founded|All my hope on God is founded]]\" ([[Joachim Neander]], c. 1680)\n*\"[[Jesu, Joy of Man's Desiring]]\" (Martin Jahn, 1661)\n*\"O Gladsome Light\" ([[Phos Hilaron]])\n*\"O Sacred Head, sore wounded\" (Paulus Gerhardt, 1656)\n*\"O Splendour of God's Glory Bright\" (Ambrose, 4th century)\n*\"When morning gilds the skies\" (stanza 3; Katholisches Gesangbuch, 1744)\n\n==Major works==\nDates given are of first publication and significant revisions.\n\n===Poetry collections===\n*The Growth of Love (1876; 1889; 1898), a sequence of (24; 79; 69) sonnets\n*Prometheus the Firegiver: A Mask in the Greek Manner (1883)\n*[[Eros and Psyche (Robert Bridges)|Eros and Psyche: A Narrative Poem in Twelve Measures]] (1885; 1894), a story from the Latin of Apuleius\n*Shorter Poems, Books I\u2013IV (1890)\n*Shorter Poems, Books I\u2013V (1894)\n*New Poems (1899)\n*Demeter: A Mask (1905), performed in 1904 at the opening of the [[Somerville College Library]]\n*Ibant Obscuri: An Experiment in the Classical Hexameter (1916), with reprint of summary of Stone's Prosody, accompanied by 'later observations & modifications'\n*October and Other Poems (1920)\n*The Tapestry: Poems (1925), in [[neo-Miltonic syllabics]]\n*New Verse (1926), includes verse of ''The Tapestry''\n*The Testament of Beauty (1929)\n\n===Verse drama===\n*Nero (1885), an historical tragedy; called ''The First Part of Nero'' subsequent to the publication of ''Nero: Part II''\n*The Feast of Bacchus (1889); partly translated from the ''Heauton-Timoroumenos'' of [[Terence]]\n*Achilles in Scyros (1890), a drama in a mixed manner\n*Palicio (1890), a romantic drama in five acts in the Elizabethan manner\n*The Return of Ulysses (1890), a drama in five acts in a mixed manner\n*The Christian Captives (1890), a tragedy in five acts in a mixed manner; on the same subject as [[Pedro Calder\u00f3n de la Barca|Calder\u00f3n]]'s ''El Principe Constante''\n*The Humours of the Court (1893), a comedy in three acts; founded on Calder\u00f3n's ''El secreto \u00e1 voces'' and on [[Lope de Vega]]'s ''El Perro del hortelano''\n*Nero, Part II (1894)\n\n===Prose===\n*[[Milton's Prosody (book)|Milton's Prosody, With a Chapter on Accentual Verse]] (1893; 1901; 1921), based on essays published in 1887 and 1889\n*Keats (1895)\n*Hymns from the Yattendon Hymnal (1899)\n*The Spirit of Man (1916)\n*Poems of Gerard Manley Hopkins (1918), edited with notes by R.B.\n*The Necessity of Poetry (1918)\n*Collected Essays, Papers, Etc. (1927\u201336)\n\n==See also==\n*[[Robert Bridges' theory of elision]]\n*[[Bridges' analysis of Milton's later work]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* Bridges, Robert: ''The Poetical Works of Robert Bridges'', Oxford Editions of Standard Authors, Oxford University Press, 2nd edition, 1936. (reissued 1953 with ''The Testament of Beauty'')\n* Gu\u00e9rard, Albert, Jr.: ''Robert Bridges: A Study of Traditionalism in Poetry'', Harvard University Press, 1942.\n* Phillips, Catherine: ''Robert Bridges: A Biography'', Oxford University Press, 1992.  {{ISBN|0-19-212251-7}}\n* Stanford, Donald E.: ''In the Classic Mode: The Achievement of Robert Bridges'', Associated University Presses, 1978. {{ISBN|0-87413-118-9}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{wikisource-author}}\n* {{Gutenberg author |id=5418}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Robert Seymour Bridges}}\n* {{Librivox author |id=277}}\n* [http://www.poetsgraves.co.uk/bridges.htm Robert Bridges' Grave]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=British [[Poet Laureate]]|before=[[Alfred Austin]]|after=[[John Masefield]]|years=1913&ndash;1930}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Poets Laureate of the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bridges, Robert}}\n[[Category:1844 births]]\n[[Category:1930 deaths]]\n[[Category:English Anglicans]]\n[[Category:British Poets Laureate]]\n[[Category:People from Walmer]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Corpus Christi College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Medical College of St Bartholomew's Hospital]]\n[[Category:19th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:Victorian poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century English poets]]\n[[Category:People from Yattendon]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n", "name_user": "Charles Matthews", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal and professional life:rm stray refs", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Bridges"}
{"title_page": "Navy\u2013Notre Dame football rivalry", "text_new": "{{Infobox sports rivalry\n| wide                  = yes\n| name                  = Navy\u2013Notre Dame football rivalry\n| image                 = \n| image_size            = \n| caption               = \n| team1                 = [[Navy Midshipmen football|Navy Midshipmen]]\n| team1logo             = Navy Athletics logo.svg\n| team2                 = [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish football|Notre Dame Fighting Irish]]\n| team2logo             = Notre Dame Fighting Irish logo.svg\n| sport                 = \n| firstmeeting          = October 15, 1927\n| mostrecent            = November 16, 2019\n| nextmeeting           = August 29, 2020\n| total                 = 93\n| series                = Notre Dame leads, 77\u201313\u20131 ({{Winning percentage|77|13|1}})\n| largestvictory        = Notre Dame, 56\u20137 (1970)\n| longeststreak         = Notre Dame, 43 (1964\u20132006)\n| currentstreak         = Notre Dame, 3 (2017\u2013present)\n| stadiums              = [[Notre Dame Stadium]] (2019, 2021)<br>[[Aviva Stadium]] (2020)<br>[[MetLife Stadium]] (2022)\n| trophy                = None (1927\u20132010)<br>Rip Miller Trophy (2011\u2013present)\n| trophy series         = Notre Dame leads, 5\u20131 ({{Winning percentage|5|1}})\n| map_location          = \n| map_width             = \n| map_label1            = \n| map_mark1             = \n| map_label1_position   = \n| coordinates1          = \n| map_label2            = \n| map_mark2             = \n| map_label2_position   = \n| coordinates2          = \n| map_caption           = \n}}\n{{OSM Location map      \n| nolabels = 1        \n| coord = {{coord|39.7845|-81.19}}\n| zoom = 5\n| width = 295 \n| height = 250\n| caption = Locations of Notre Dame and Navy\n| mark1 = Gold pog.svg\n| label1 = Notre Dame\n| mark-coord1 = {{Coord|41.698|-86.234}}\n| label-pos1 = right\n| label-color1 = black\n| mark2 = Blue pog.svg\n| label2 = Navy\n| mark-coord2 = {{Coord|38.983|-76.485}}\n| label-pos2 = top\n| label-color2 = black\n}}\n\nThe '''Navy\u2013Notre Dame football rivalry''' is an American [[college football]] [[college rivalry|rivalry]] between the [[Navy Midshipmen football]] team of the [[United States Naval Academy]] and [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish football]] team of the [[University of Notre Dame]]. It has been played annually since 1927, making it the longest uninterrupted intersectional rivalry in college football,<ref name=\"ND Navy Renewal\"/> and the third-longest never-interrupted college football rivalry overall, after only Minnesota vs. Wisconsin (uninterrupted since 1907) and Kansas State vs. Iowa State (uninterrupted since 1917).\n\nNotre Dame leads the series 77\u201313\u20131.<ref>https://und.com/16-irish-cruise-to-52-20-victory-over-23-navy/</ref> Before Navy won a 46\u201344 triple-overtime contest in 2007, Notre Dame had a 43-game winning streak that was the [[Most consecutive wins over one opponent (NCAA football)|longest series win streak]] between two annual opponents in the history of Division I FBS football.<ref name=\"ND 44 Navy 46\">{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=273070087|title=Notre Dame's NCAA-record 43-game win streak over Navy ends|publisher=espn.com|accessdate=2008-05-05}}</ref> Navy's previous win came in 1963, 35\u201314 with future [[Heisman Trophy]] winner and NFL QB [[Roger Staubach]] at the helm. Navy had come close to winning on numerous occasions before 2007. The Midshipmen subsequently won again in 2009, 2010 and 2016.\n\nThough the game is often played at [[Notre Dame Stadium]] in South Bend, it has never been played at [[Navy\u2013Marine Corps Memorial Stadium]], due to its relatively small size. Instead, Navy usually hosts the game at larger facilities such as Baltimore's old [[Memorial Stadium (Baltimore)|Memorial Stadium]] or current [[M&T Bank Stadium]], [[FedExField]] in [[Landover, Maryland]], or at [[Giants Stadium]] in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]]. From 1960 to 1970, the Midshipmen hosted the game at [[John F. Kennedy Stadium]] in Philadelphia, and they hosted the 1972, 1974 and 1993 games at Philadelphia's [[Veterans Stadium]]. The game has been played twice in [[Dublin]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\u2014in 1996 at [[Croke Park]] and 2012 at [[Aviva Stadium]].<ref name=\"Aviva Host Navy ND\">{{cite web| url=http://www.navysports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/092110aaa.html |title=Aviva Stadium To Host The 2012 Navy-Notre Dame Game |publisher=navysports.com |date=2010-09-01 |accessdate=2010-09-23}}</ref> The game was also occasionally played at old [[Cleveland Stadium]].  The 2016 game was held at [[EverBank Field]] in [[Jacksonville, Florida]]. <ref name=\"Notre Dame Athletics website\">{{cite web|url=http://www.und.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/070815aai.html|website=und.com|accessdate=10 October 2015}}</ref> Navy's 2018 home game was played at [[Qualcomm Stadium]] in [[San Diego, California]] (the first time the teams have played each other west of the [[Eastern Time Zone]]), and the 2020 game will be at [[Aviva Stadium]] in [[Dublin]], [[Ireland]].<ref>https://und.com/news/2018/10/25/football-dublins-aviva-stadium-to-host-the-2020-navy-notre-dame-game.aspx</ref>\n\n==History==\nDespite the one-sided result the last few decades, most Notre Dame and Navy fans consider the series a sacred tradition for historical reasons. Both schools have strong football traditions going back to the beginnings of the sport. Notre Dame, like many colleges, faced severe financial difficulties during World War II, which were exacerbated by the fact that it was then still an all-male institution. The US Navy made Notre Dame [[V-12 Navy College Training Program|a training center for V-12 candidates]] and paid enough for usage of the facilities to keep the University afloat. Notre Dame has since extended an open invitation for Navy to play the Fighting Irish in football and considers the game annual repayment on a debt of honor. The series is marked by mutual respect, as evidenced by each team standing at attention during the playing of the other's alma mater after the game, a tradition that started in 2005. Navy's athletic director, on renewing the series through 2016, remarked \"...it is of great interest to our collective national audience of Fighting Irish fans, Naval Academy alumni, and the Navy family at large.\"<ref name=\"ND Navy Renewal\">{{cite web| url=http://und.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/111005aac.html |title=Notre Dame And Navy Extend Series 10 More Years |publisher=und.cstv.com |date=2005-11-10 |accessdate=2008-05-05}}</ref> The series is scheduled to continue indefinitely; renewals are a mere formality.<ref name=\"ND Navy Renewal\"/>\n\n===The Streak===\nNotre Dame's NCAA-record 43-game win streak against Navy began in 1964:\n* 1964 \u2013 Notre Dame 40, Navy 0: Notre Dame came in at 5\u20130 under first year coach [[Ara Parseghian]] and  shut out the Midshipmen in a game that pitted 1963 Heisman Trophy winner Roger Staubach against 1964 winner John Huarte.\n* 1969 \u2013 Notre Dame 47, Navy 0: The Irish set a still-standing, single-game school record of 720 total offensive yards.\n* 1974 \u2013 Notre Dame 14, Navy 6: For three quarters, Navy kept the Fighting Irish offense in check with its punting game and led 6\u20130 going into the fourth quarter. Notre Dame quarterback Tom Clements threw a touchdown pass to Pete Demmerle to put the Fighting Irish in front, then Randy Harrison added an insurance touchdown with an interception return.  Unbeknownst to anyone at the time, Irish coach Ara Parseghian privately decided to resign at the end of the season after this game.\n* 1976 \u2013 Notre Dame 27, Navy 21: Irish defensive back Dave Waymer tipped away a fourth down pass in the end zone late in the game to preserve the win for Notre Dame.\n* 1984 \u2013 Notre Dame 18, Navy 17: John Carney's field goal with 14 seconds left erased a 17\u20137 deficit.  The officials failed to notice that the play clock had expired before the ball was snapped.\n* 1991 \u2013 Notre Dame 38, Navy 0:  Notre Dame's 700th victory.\n* 1997 \u2013 Notre Dame 21, Navy 17: Allen Rossum saved the day for the Fighting Irish, knocking Navy receiver Pat McGrew out of bounds at the 1-yard line on a 69-yard pass as time ran out.\n* 1999 \u2013 Notre Dame 28, Navy 24: Notre Dame needed a 1st down on 4th and 9 with 1:37 left. They failed to convert but an errant spot allowed the Irish to keep possession and eventually score to escape with a 28\u201324 win.\n* 2002 \u2013 Notre Dame 30, Navy 23: Notre Dame, coming off a 14\u20137 upset loss to Boston College, scored 15 unanswered points late in the fourth quarter to win under first-year head coach Tyrone Willingham.\n* 2003 \u2013 Notre Dame 27, Navy 24: D. J. Fitzpatrick's 40-yard field goal as time expired lifted the Fighting Irish over Navy.\n* 2007 \u2013 [[2007 Navy vs. Notre Dame football game|Navy 46, Notre Dame 44 (3OT)]] \u2013 After 43 years, Navy beat Notre Dame in triple overtime.\n\n==Game results==\n{{Sports rivalry series table\n| format = compact | cols = 2 | series_summary = yes\n| team1 = Navy\n| team1style = {{NCAA secondary color cell|Navy Midshipmen}}\n| team2 = Notre Dame\n| team2style = {{NCAA color cell|Notre Dame Fighting Irish}}\n| legend_forfeit_text = Vacated wins{{#tag:ref|Notre Dame's wins in 2012 and 2013 were vacated as a result of NCAA sanctions against the Notre Dame football program issued on November 22, 2016 after the NCAA found that a student-trainer committed academic misconduct for two football players and provided six other players with impermissible academic extra benefits. The NCAA also rejected Notre Dame's appeal on February 13, 2018. This win is not included in Notre Dame's all-time record, nor is it counted in the series record between the two teams.<ref name=\"ESPNSanctions2\">[http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/18113811/ncaa-orders-notre-dame-fighting-irish-vacate-wins-2012-2013-seasons NCAA orders Notre Dame Fighting Irish to vacate wins from 2012, 2013 seasons]. [[ESPN]], 2016-11-22.</ref> See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject College football/Vacated victories]] for an explanation of how vacated victories are recorded.<ref name=\"Low, Chris\">{{cite web |author=Low, Chris |date=June 16, 2009 |title=What does vacating wins really mean? |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/ncfnation/post/_/id/4734/what-does-vacating-wins-really-mean |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Taylor, John\">{{cite web |author=Taylor, John |date=July 4, 2009 |title=Vacated Wins Do Not Equal Forfeits |url=http://collegefootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2009/07/04/vacated-wins-do-not-equal-forfeits/ |work=NBCSports.com |publisher=NBC Sports |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref>|group=\"n\"|name=\"vacation 2\"}}\n| October 15, 1927 | [[Baltimore|Baltimore, MD]] | Notre Dame | 19 | Navy | 6\n| October 13, 1928 | [[Chicago|Chicago, IL]] | Notre Dame | 7 | Navy | 0\n| October 12, 1929 | Baltimore, MD | Notre Dame | 14 | Navy | 7\n| October 11, 1930 | [[South Bend, Indiana|South Bend, IN]] | Notre Dame | 26 | Navy | 2\n| November 14, 1931 | Baltimore, MD | Notre Dame | 20 | Navy | 0\n| November 19, 1932 | [[Cleveland|Cleveland, OH]] | Notre Dame | 12 | Navy | 0\n| November 4, 1933 | Baltimore, MD | Navy | 7 | Notre Dame | 0\n| November 10, 1934 | Cleveland, OH | Navy | 10 | Notre Dame | 6\n| October 26, 1935 | Baltimore, MD | Notre Dame | 14 | Navy | 0\n| November 7, 1936 | Baltimore, MD | Navy | 3 | #13 Notre Dame | 0\n| October 23, 1937 | South Bend, IN | Notre Dame | 9 | Navy | 7\n| November 5, 1938 | Baltimore, MD | #4 Notre Dame | 15 | Navy | 0\n| October 21, 1939 | Cleveland, OH | #2 Notre Dame | 14 | Navy | 7\n| November 9, 1940 | Baltimore, MD | #7 Notre Dame | 13 | Navy | 7\n| November 8, 1941 | Baltimore, MD | #7 Notre Dame | 20 | #6 Navy | 13\n| October 31, 1942 | Cleveland, OH | #4 Notre Dame | 9 | Navy |