 Bend, IN | #12 Notre Dame | 21 | Navy | 0\n| November 4, 1972 | Philadelphia, PA | #12 Notre Dame | 42 | Navy | 23\n| November 3, 1973 | South Bend, IN | #5 Notre Dame | 44 | Navy | 7\n| November 2, 1974 | Philadelphia, PA | #7 Notre Dame | 14 | Navy | 6\n| November 1, 1975 | South Bend, IN | #15 Notre Dame | 31 | Navy | 10\n| October 30, 1976 | Cleveland, OH | #11 Notre Dame | 27 | Navy | 21\n| October 29, 1977 | South Bend, IN | #5 Notre Dame | 43 | Navy | 10\n| November 4, 1978 | Cleveland, OH | #15 Notre Dame | 27 | #11 Navy | 7\n| November 3, 1979 | South Bend, IN | #13 Notre Dame | 14 | Navy | 0\n| November 1, 1980 | [[East Rutherford, New Jersey|East Rutherford, NJ]] | #3 Notre Dame | 33 | Navy | 0\n| October 31, 1981 | South Bend, IN | Notre Dame | 38 | Navy | 0\n| October 30, 1982 | East Rutherford, NJ | Notre Dame | 27 | Navy | 10\n| October 29, 1983 | South Bend, IN | #19 Notre Dame | 28 | Navy | 12\n| November 3, 1984 | East Rutherford, NJ | Notre Dame | 18 | Navy | 17\n| November 2, 1985 | South Bend, IN | Notre Dame | 41 | Navy | 17\n| November 1, 1986 | Baltimore, MD | Notre Dame | 33 | Navy | 14\n| October 31, 1987 | South Bend, IN | #9 Notre Dame | 56 | Navy | 13\n| October 29, 1988 | Baltimore, MD | #2 Notre Dame | 22 | Navy | 7\n| November 4, 1989 | South Bend, IN | #1 Notre Dame | 41 | Navy | 0\n| November 3, 1990 | East Rutherford, NJ | #2 Notre Dame | 52 | Navy | 31\n| November 2, 1991 | South Bend, IN | #5 Notre Dame | 38 | Navy | 0\n| October 31, 1992 | East Rutherford, NJ | #10 Notre Dame | 38 | Navy | 7\n| October 30, 1993 | Philadelphia, PA | #2 Notre Dame | 58 | Navy | 27\n| October 29, 1994 | South Bend, IN | Notre Dame | 58 | Navy | 21\n| November 4, 1995 | South Bend, IN | #8 Notre Dame | 35 | Navy | 17\n| November 2, 1996 | [[Dublin|Dublin, Ireland]] | #19 Notre Dame | 54 | Navy | 27\n| November 1, 1997 | South Bend, IN | Notre Dame | 21 | Navy | 17\n| November 14, 1998 | [[Landover, Maryland|Landover, MD]] | #12 Notre Dame | 30 | Navy | 0\n| October 30, 1999 | South Bend, IN | Notre Dame | 28 | Navy | 24\n| October 14, 2000 | [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando, FL]] | #20 Notre Dame | 45 | Navy | 14\n| November 17, 2001 | South Bend, IN | Notre Dame | 34 | Navy | 16\n| November 9, 2002 | Baltimore, MD | #9 Notre Dame | 30 | Navy | 23\n| November 8, 2003 | South Bend, IN | Notre Dame | 27 | Navy | 24\n| October 16, 2004 | East Rutherford, NJ | Notre Dame | 27 | Navy | 9\n| November 12, 2005 | South Bend, IN | #7 Notre Dame | 42 | Navy | 21\n| October 28, 2006 | Baltimore, MD | #11 Notre Dame | 38 | Navy | 14\n| [[2007 Navy vs. Notre Dame football game|November 3, 2007]] | South Bend, IN | Navy | 46 | Notre Dame | 44<sup>3OT</sup>\n| November 15, 2008 | Baltimore, MD | Notre Dame | 27 | Navy | 21\n| November 7, 2009 | South Bend, IN | Navy | 23 | Notre Dame | 21\n| October 23, 2010 | East Rutherford, NJ | Navy | 35 | Notre Dame | 17\n| October 29, 2011 | South Bend, IN | Navy | 14 | Notre Dame | 56\n| September 1, 2012 | Dublin, Ireland | Navy | 10 | Notre Dame<sup>\u2020</sup> | 50\n| November 2, 2013 | South Bend, IN | Notre Dame<sup>\u2020</sup> | 38 | Navy | 34\n| November 1, 2014 | Landover, MD | #6 Notre Dame | 49 | Navy | 39\n| October 10, 2015 | South Bend, IN | #15 Notre Dame | 41 | Navy | 24\n| November 5, 2016 | [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville, FL]] | Navy | 28 | Notre Dame | 27\n| November 18, 2017 | South Bend, IN | #9 Notre Dame | 24 | Navy | 17\n| October 27, 2018  | [[San Diego|San Diego, CA]] | #3 Notre Dame | 44 | Navy | 22\n| November 16, 2019 | South Bend, IN | #16 Notre Dame| 52 | #23 Navy | 20\n| August 29, 2020 | Dublin, Ireland | | | |-->\n| note = \u2020 Vacated by Notre Dame.\n}}\n\n==Television==\nIn years when Navy hosts (even-numbered), [[ESPN]] holds rights to the game as part of an expanded deal with Navy's [[American Athletic Conference]] to take effect in the 2020-21 season.<ref>{{cite news |title=American Athletic Conference and ESPN Agree to 12-Year Media Rights Extension |url=http://theamerican.org/news/2019/3/27/general-american-athletic-conference-and-espn-agree-to-12-year-media-rights-extension.aspx |work=www.theamerican.org |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn years when Notre Dame hosts (odd-numbered), it is carried on [[Notre Dame Football on NBC|NBC]] as are other Notre Dame home games.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|American football|College football}}\n* [[List of NCAA college football rivalry games]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Navy Midshipmen football navbox}}\n{{Notre Dame Fighting Irish football navbox}}\n{{Notre Dame Fighting Irish rivalry navbox}}\n{{American Athletic Conference football rivalry navbox}}\n{{NCAA Division I FBS independents rivalry navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Navy-Notre Dame football rivalry}}\n[[Category:College football rivalries in the United States]]\n[[Category:Navy Midshipmen football]]\n[[Category:Notre Dame Fighting Irish football]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sports rivalry\n| wide                  = yes\n| name                  = Navy\u2013Notre Dame football rivalry\n| image                 = \n| image_size            = \n| caption               = \n| team1                 = [[Navy Midshipmen football|Navy Midshipmen]]\n| team1logo             = Navy Athletics logo.svg\n| team2                 = [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish football|Notre Dame Fighting Irish]]\n| team2logo             = Notre Dame Fighting Irish logo.svg\n| sport                 = \n| firstmeeting          = October 15, 1927\n| mostrecent            = November 16, 2019\n| nextmeeting           = August 29, 2020\n| total                 = 93\n| series                = Notre Dame leads, 77\u201313\u20131 ({{Winning percentage|77|13|1}})\n| largestvictory        = Notre Dame, 56\u20137 (1970)\n| longeststreak         = Notre Dame, 43 (1964\u20132006)\n| currentstreak         = Notre Dame, 3 (2017\u2013present)\n| stadiums              = [[Notre Dame Stadium]] (2019, 2021)<br>[[Aviva Stadium]] (2020)<br>[[MetLife Stadium]] (2022)\n| trophy                = None (1927\u20132010)<br>Rip Miller Trophy (2011\u2013present)\n| trophy series         = Notre Dame leads, 5\u20131 ({{Winning percentage|5|1}})\n| map_location          = \n| map_width             = \n| map_label1            = \n| map_mark1             = \n| map_label1_position   = \n| coordinates1          = \n| map_label2            = \n| map_mark2             = \n| map_label2_position   = \n| coordinates2          = \n| map_caption           = \n}}\n{{OSM Location map      \n| nolabels = 1        \n| coord = {{coord|39.7845|-81.19}}\n| zoom = 5\n| width = 295 \n| height = 250\n| caption = Locations of Notre Dame and Navy\n| mark1 = Gold pog.svg\n| label1 = Notre Dame\n| mark-coord1 = {{Coord|41.698|-86.234}}\n| label-pos1 = right\n| label-color1 = black\n| mark2 = Blue pog.svg\n| label2 = Navy\n| mark-coord2 = {{Coord|38.983|-76.485}}\n| label-pos2 = top\n| label-color2 = black\n}}\n\nThe '''Navy\u2013Notre Dame football rivalry''' is an American [[college football]] [[college rivalry|rivalry]] between the [[Navy Midshipmen football]] team of the [[United States Naval Academy]] and [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish football]] team of the [[University of Notre Dame]]. It has been played annually since 1927, making it the longest uninterrupted intersectional rivalry in college football,<ref name=\"ND Navy Renewal\"/> and the third-longest never-interrupted college football rivalry overall, after only Minnesota vs. Wisconsin (uninterrupted since 1907) and Kansas State vs. Iowa State (uninterrupted since 1917).\n\nNotre Dame leads the series 77\u201313\u20131.<ref>https://und.com/16-irish-cruise-to-52-20-victory-over-23-navy/</ref> Before Navy won a 46\u201344 triple-overtime contest in 2007, Notre Dame had a 43-game winning streak that was the [[Most consecutive wins over one opponent (NCAA football)|longest series win streak]] between two annual opponents in the history of Division I FBS football.<ref name=\"ND 44 Navy 46\">{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=273070087|title=Notre Dame's NCAA-record 43-game win streak over Navy ends|publisher=espn.com|accessdate=2008-05-05}}</ref> Navy's previous win came in 1963, 35\u201314 with future [[Heisman Trophy]] winner and NFL QB [[Roger Staubach]] at the helm. Navy had come close to winning on numerous occasions before 2007. The Midshipmen subsequently won again in 2009, 2010 and 2016.\n\nThough the game is often played at [[Notre Dame Stadium]] in South Bend, it has never been played at [[Navy\u2013Marine Corps Memorial Stadium]], due to its relatively small size. Instead, Navy usually hosts the game at larger facilities such as Baltimore's old [[Memorial Stadium (Baltimore)|Memorial Stadium]] or current [[M&T Bank Stadium]], [[FedExField]] in [[Landover, Maryland]], or at [[Giants Stadium]] in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]]. From 1960 to 1970, the Midshipmen hosted the game at [[John F. Kennedy Stadium]] in Philadelphia, and they hosted the 1972, 1974 and 1993 games at Philadelphia's [[Veterans Stadium]]. The game has been played twice in [[Dublin]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\u2014in 1996 at [[Croke Park]] and 2012 at [[Aviva Stadium]].<ref name=\"Aviva Host Navy ND\">{{cite web| url=http://www.navysports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/092110aaa.html |title=Aviva Stadium To Host The 2012 Navy-Notre Dame Game |publisher=navysports.com |date=2010-09-01 |accessdate=2010-09-23}}</ref> The game was also occasionally played at old [[Cleveland Stadium]].  The 2016 game was held at [[EverBank Field]] in [[Jacksonville, Florida]]. <ref name=\"Notre Dame Athletics website\">{{cite web|url=http://www.und.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/070815aai.html|website=und.com|accessdate=10 October 2015}}</ref> Navy's 2018 home game was played at [[Qualcomm Stadium]] in [[San Diego, California]] (the first time the teams have played each other west of the [[Eastern Time Zone]]), and the 2020 game will be at [[Aviva Stadium]] in [[Dublin]], [[Ireland]].<ref>https://und.com/news/2018/10/25/football-dublins-aviva-stadium-to-host-the-2020-navy-notre-dame-game.aspx</ref>\n\n==History==\nDespite the one-sided result the last few decades, most Notre Dame and Navy fans consider the series a sacred tradition for historical reasons. Both schools have strong football traditions going back to the beginnings of the sport. Notre Dame, like many colleges, faced severe financial difficulties during World War II, which were exacerbated by the fact that it was then still an all-male institution. The US Navy made Notre Dame [[V-12 Navy College Training Program|a training center for V-12 candidates]] and paid enough for usage of the facilities to keep the University afloat. Notre Dame has since extended an open invitation for Navy to play the Fighting Irish in football and considers the game annual repayment on a debt of honor. The series is marked by mutual respect, as evidenced by each team standing at attention during the playing of the other's alma mater after the game, a tradition that started in 2005. Navy's athletic director, on renewing the series through 2016, remarked \"...it is of great interest to our collective national audience of Fighting Irish fans, Naval Academy alumni, and the Navy family at large.\"<ref name=\"ND Navy Renewal\">{{cite web| url=http://und.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/111005aac.html |title=Notre Dame And Navy Extend Series 10 More Years |publisher=und.cstv.com |date=2005-11-10 |accessdate=2008-05-05}}</ref> The series is scheduled to continue indefinitely; renewals are a mere formality.<ref name=\"ND Navy Renewal\"/>\n\n===The Streak===\nNotre Dame's NCAA-record 43-game win streak against Navy began in 1964:\n* 1964 \u2013 Notre Dame 40, Navy 0: Notre Dame came in at 5\u20130 under first year coach [[Ara Parseghian]] and  shut out the Midshipmen in a game that pitted 1963 Heisman Trophy winner Roger Staubach against 1964 winner John Huarte.\n* 1969 \u2013 Notre Dame 47, Navy 0: The Irish set a still-standing, single-game school record of 720 total offensive yards.\n* 1974 \u2013 Notre Dame 14, Navy 6: For three quarters, Navy kept the Fighting Irish offense in check with its punting game and led 6\u20130 going into the fourth quarter. Notre Dame quarterback Tom Clements threw a touchdown pass to Pete Demmerle to put the Fighting Irish in front, then Randy Harrison added an insurance touchdown with an interception return.  Unbeknownst to anyone at the time, Irish coach Ara Parseghian privately decided to resign at the end of the season after this game.\n* 1976 \u2013 Notre Dame 27, Navy 21: Irish defensive back Dave Waymer tipped away a fourth down pass in the end zone late in the game to preserve the win for Notre Dame.\n* 1984 \u2013 Notre Dame 18, Navy 17: John Carney's field goal with 14 seconds left erased a 17\u20137 deficit.  The officials failed to notice that the play clock had expired before the ball was snapped.\n* 1991 \u2013 Notre Dame 38, Navy 0:  Notre Dame's 700th victory.\n* 1997 \u2013 Notre Dame 21, Navy 17: Allen Rossum saved the day for the Fighting Irish, knocking Navy receiver Pat McGrew out of bounds at the 1-yard line on a 69-yard pass as time ran out.\n* 1999 \u2013 Notre Dame 28, Navy 24: Notre Dame needed a 1st down on 4th and 9 with 1:37 left. They failed to convert but an errant spot allowed the Irish to keep possession and eventually score to escape with a 28\u201324 win.\n* 2002 \u2013 Notre Dame 30, Navy 23: Notre Dame, coming off a 14\u20137 upset loss to Boston College, scored 15 unanswered points late in the fourth quarter to win under first-year head coach Tyrone Willingham.\n* 2003 \u2013 Notre Dame 27, Navy 24: D. J. Fitzpatrick's 40-yard field goal as time expired lifted the Fighting Irish over Navy.\n* 2007 \u2013 [[2007 Navy vs. Notre Dame football game|Navy 46, Notre Dame 44 (3OT)]] \u2013 After 43 years, Navy beat Notre Dame in triple overtime.\n\n==Game results==\n{{Sports rivalry series table\n| format = compact | cols = 2 | series_summary = yes\n| team1 = Navy\n| team1style = {{NCAA secondary color cell|Navy Midshipmen}}\n| team2 = Notre Dame\n| team2style = {{NCAA color cell|Notre Dame Fighting Irish}}\n| legend_forfeit_text = Vacated wins{{#tag:ref|Notre Dame's wins in 2012 and 2013 were vacated as a result of NCAA sanctions against the Notre Dame football program issued on November 22, 2016 after the NCAA found that a student-trainer committed academic misconduct for two football players and provided six other players with impermissible academic extra benefits. The NCAA also rejected Notre Dame's appeal on February 13, 2018. This win is not included in Notre Dame's all-time record, nor is it counted in the series record between the two teams.<ref name=\"ESPNSanctions2\">[http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/18113811/ncaa-orders-notre-dame-fighting-irish-vacate-wins-2012-2013-seasons NCAA orders Notre Dame Fighting Irish to vacate wins from 2012, 2013 seasons]. [[ESPN]], 2016-11-22.</ref> See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject College football/Vacated victories]] for an explanation of how vacated victories are recorded.<ref name=\"Low, Chris\">{{cite web |author=Low, Chris |date=June 16, 2009 |title=What does vacating wins really mean? |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/ncfnation/post/_/id/4734/what-does-vacating-wins-really-mean |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Taylor, John\">{{cite web |author=Taylor, John |date=July 4, 2009 |title=Vacated Wins Do Not Equal Forfeits |url=http://collegefootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2009/07/04/vacated-wins-do-not-equal-forfeits/ |work=NBCSports.com |publisher=NBC Sports |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref>|group=\"n\"|name=\"vacation 2\"}}\n| October 15, 1927 | Baltimore, MD | Notre Dame | 19 | Navy | 6\n| October 13, 1928 | Chicago, IL | Notre Dame | 7 | Navy | 0\n| October 12, 1929 | Baltimore, MD | Notre Dame | 14 | Navy | 7\n| October 11, 1930 | South Be