{"title_page": "Balian of Beirut", "text_new": "{{other people||Balian of Ibelin (disambiguation)}}\n{{no footnotes|date=October 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox noble|type\n| name         = Balian\n| title        = \n| image        = Armoiries Ibelin.svg\n| image_size   = 150px\n| caption      = Coat-of-arms of Ibelin.\n| succession   = Lord of Beirut\n| reign        = \n| predecessor  = [[John of Ibelin, the Old Lord of Beirut|John I of Beirut]]\n| successor    = [[John II of Beirut]]\n| spouse       = Eschiva de Montfaucon\n| issue        = Hugh<br>[[John II of Beirut]]<br>Isabelle \n| noble family = \n| father       = [[John of Ibelin, the Old Lord of Beirut|John I of Beirut]]\n| mother       = [[Melisende of Arsuf]]\n| birth_date   = \n| birth_place  = Ascalon\n| death_date   = 1247\n}}\n\n'''Balian of Beirut''' (died 1247) was the [[Lord of Beirut]], the second of his family, from 1236, and a son of the famous [[John of Ibelin, the Old Lord of Beirut|\"Old Lord\" John of Ibelin]], by his second wife [[Melisende of Arsuf]]. From his father he assumed the leadership of the nobility in the [[War of the Lombards]], fought against the agents of the [[Emperor Frederick II]]. \n\nHe was a warrior from an early age. At the [[Battle of Agridi]] in 1232, though he was supposed to be in the rearguard with his father and the [[King of Cyprus]], he instead went to the front, beside either [[Hugh of Ibelin (died 1238)|Hugh of Ibelin]] and [[Anceau of Brie]], commanders of the first and second [[Battle (formation)|battles]]. At the battle, Balian won fame defending a pass from the [[Lombardy|Lombards]]. A story is told in the ''[[Gestes des Chiprois]]'' that Balian once struck a Lombard knight so hard that he himself was dismounted. \n\nBalian led his family in besieging [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]] in 1242. He also had the support of [[Philip of Novara]] and [[Philip of Montfort, Lord of Tyre|Philip of Montfort]] and he employed mercenaries and galleys in the endeavour. \n\nBalian of Ibelin, lord of Beirut married Eschiva de Montfaucon, daughter of [[Walter of Montb\u00e9liard]] and Bourgogne de Lusignan of Cyprus and they had issue:\n* Hugue 1231/32-1254/55, married (1250/53) to Marie of Montb\u00e9liard.\n* [[John II of Beirut]] died 1264, married to Alice de la Roche, daughter of [[Guy de la Roche|Guy, Duke of Athens]].\n* Isabelle, married (c. 1250) to Henri Embriaco de Giblet (died c. 1271).\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n| 1= '''Balian d'Ibelin, lord of Beirut'''\n| 2= [[John of Ibelin, the Old Lord of Beirut|John I d'Ibelin, lord of Beirut]]\n| 3= [[Melisende of Arsuf|Melisende, lady of Arsuf]]\n| 4= [[Balian of Ibelin|Balian d'Ibelin]]\n| 5= [[Maria Komnene, Queen of Jerusalem|Maria Komnene]]\n| 6= Guy of Arsuf\n| 7= \n| 8= [[Barisan of Ibelin|Barisan d'Ibelin]]\n| 9= Helvis, lady of Ramla\n|10= [[John Doukas Komnenos|John Komnenos]]\n|11= Maria Taronitissa\n|12=\n|13= \n|14= \n|15= \n|16= \n|17= \n|18= [[Baldwin I of Ramla|Baldwin I, lord of Ramla]]\n|19= Stephanie of Nablus\n|20= [[Andronikos Komnenos (son of John II)|Andronikos Komnenos]]\n|21= Eirene Aineiadissa\n|22= John Taronites\n|23= \n|24= \n|25= \n|26= \n|27= \n|28= \n|29= \n|30= \n|31= \n}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John I of Beirut]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lord_of_Beirut#Lordship_of_Beirut|Lord of Beirut]]|years=1236\u20131247}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Hugh of Beirut]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n*Marshall, Christopher. ''Warfare in the Latin East, 1192&ndash;1291''. Cambridge University Press, 1992.\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Balian of Beirut}}\n\n[[Category:Christians of the Crusades]]\n[[Category:Christians of the Barons' Crusade]]\n[[Category:1247 deaths]]\n[[Category:House of Ibelin]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:History of Beirut]]\n[[Category:13th-century rulers]]\n{{noble-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{other people||Balian of Ibelin (disambiguation)}}\n{{no footnotes|date=October 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox noble|type\n| name         = Balian\n| title        = \n| image        = Armoiries Ibelin.svg\n| image_size   = 150px\n| caption      = Coat-of-arms of Ibelin.\n| succession   = Lord of Beirut\n| reign        = \n| predecessor  = [[John of Ibelin, the Old Lord of Beirut|John I of Beirut]]\n| successor    = [[John II of Beirut]]\n| spouse       = Eschiva de Montfaucon\n| issue        = Hugh<br>[[John II of Beirut]]<br>Isabelle \n| noble family = \n| father       = [[John of Ibelin, the Old Lord of Beirut|John I of Beirut]]\n| mother       = [[Melisende of Arsuf]]\n| birth_date   = \n| birth_place  = Ascalon\n| death_date   = 1247\n}}\n\n'''Balian of Beirut''' (died 1247) was the [[Lord of Beirut]], the second of his family, from 1236, and a son of the famous [[John of Ibelin, the Old Lord of Beirut|\"Old Lord\" John of Ibelin]], by his second wife [[Melisende of Arsuf]]. From his father he assumed the leadership of the nobility in the [[War of the Lombards]], fought against the agents of the [[Emperor Frederick II]]. \n\nHe was a warrior from an early age. At the [[Battle of Agridi]] in 1232, though he was supposed to be in the rearguard with his father and the [[King of Cyprus]], he instead went to the front, beside either [[Hugh of Ibelin (died 1238)|Hugh of Ibelin]] and [[Anceau of Brie]], commanders of the first and second [[Battle (formation)|battles]]. At the battle, Balian won fame defending a pass from the [[Lombardy|Lombards]]. A story is told in the ''[[Gestes des Chiprois]]'' that Balian once struck a Lombard knight so hard that he himself was dismounted. \n\nBalian led his family in besieging [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]] in 1242. He also had the support of [[Philip of Novara]] and [[Philip of Montfort, Lord of Tyre|Philip of Montfort]] and he employed mercenaries and galleys in the endeavour. \n\nBalian of Ibelin, lord of Beirut married Eschiva de Montfaucon, daughter of [[Walter of Montb\u00e9liard]] and Bourgogne de Lusignan of Cyprus and they had issue:\n* Hugue 1231/32-1254/55, married (1250/53) to Marie of Montb\u00e9liard.\n* [[John II of Beirut]] died 1264, married to Alice de la Roche, daughter of Duke of Athens.\n* Isabelle, married (c. 1250) to Henri Embriaco de Giblet (died c. 1271).\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n| 1= '''Balian d'Ibelin, lord of Beirut'''\n| 2= [[John of Ibelin, the Old Lord of Beirut|John I d'Ibelin, lord of Beirut]]\n| 3= [[Melisende of Arsuf|Melisende, lady of Arsuf]]\n| 4= [[Balian of Ibelin|Balian d'Ibelin]]\n| 5= [[Maria Komnene, Queen of Jerusalem|Maria Komnene]]\n| 6= Guy of Arsuf\n| 7= \n| 8= [[Barisan of Ibelin|Barisan d'Ibelin]]\n| 9= Helvis, lady of Ramla\n|10= [[John Doukas Komnenos|John Komnenos]]\n|11= Maria Taronitissa\n|12=\n|13= \n|14= \n|15= \n|16= \n|17= \n|18= [[Baldwin I of Ramla|Baldwin I, lord of Ramla]]\n|19= Stephanie of Nablus\n|20= [[Andronikos Komnenos (son of John II)|Andronikos Komnenos]]\n|21= Eirene Aineiadissa\n|22= John Taronites\n|23= \n|24= \n|25= \n|26= \n|27= \n|28= \n|29= \n|30= \n|31= \n}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John I of Beirut]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lord_of_Beirut#Lordship_of_Beirut|Lord of Beirut]]|years=1236\u20131247}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Hugh of Beirut]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n*Marshall, Christopher. ''Warfare in the Latin East, 1192&ndash;1291''. Cambridge University Press, 1992.\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Balian of Beirut}}\n\n[[Category:Christians of the Crusades]]\n[[Category:Christians of the Barons' Crusade]]\n[[Category:1247 deaths]]\n[[Category:House of Ibelin]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:History of Beirut]]\n[[Category:13th-century rulers]]\n{